\par }\pard \ql \fi-600\li600\ri0\sb120\sa120\widctlpar\tx555\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin600\itap0\pararsid6622312 {\f0\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033\insrsid6622312\charrsid4074397 I:\tab Now if I could ask you when you were born?
\par MC:\tab 1900
\par I:\tab Whereabouts was this?
\par MC:\tab Near Shelton. I think it was Leek road.
\par I:\tab What sort of a house was it?
\par MC:\tab Just an ordinary terrace house, three down, two up.
\par I:\tab It was fairly big then?
\par MC:\tab Oh no, it wasn't big. Just a front room, kitchen and scullery and two bedrooms.
\par I:\tab Had you any garden?
\par MC:\tab A little tiny square patch at the front, then back yard was a paved back yard.
\par I:\tab What had you in your kitchen?
\par MC:\tab Well, an old, a great big old sofa that my father had made out of wood. But he had made it so blessed comfortable we could all go to sleep on it. And a table and chairs and the old tin bonnet in front of th
e fire, you know, the hanger to put the plates to cook on, and a tin bonnet and all those sorts of things. Just an ordinary kitchen. And at the back of the houses was a, I think they were in the houses they were, a kitchen piece that you could slide a lit
tle table out, you could cut bread on it if you didn't want to use your scullery. Quite useful they were.
\par I:\tab Had you a stove apart from -
\par MC:\tab Just an ordinary old gas stove in the kitchen.
\par I:\tab An oven with it as well?
\par MC:\tab Well yes, like a present day, well not so good of course, perhaps a couple of lights on top and a gas oven.
\par I:\tab And would you have all your meals in it?
\par MC:\tab In the middle room. Yes.
\par I:\tab What had you in the scullery?
\par MC:\tab Oh just the old big mangle that nearly filled the scullery with a great big wheel and a tub, two tubs, one with the dolly pegs stood in, with the legs, with four legs on, the old wooden dolly peg.
\par I:\tab How did you heat water?
\par MC:\tab With a kettle on the hobs, the hobs on the fire grate in the middle room, where they always got big kettles, you used to have to black lead them to make them shine.
\par I:\tab What a job.
\par MC:\tab We'd always got those and they were always full and then when we wanted a quick cup of tea, we couldn't use the gas stove for that.
\par I:\tab So did you have a sink in your scullery?
\par MC:\tab Yes but it was one of those shallow brown things, only about 6' deep.
\par I:\tab What happened over baths?
\par MC:\tab Well we had rather a smaller one for the little ones, I was the eldest of seven you see, we had a smallish one for the little ones, that was on the
 hearth in the winter and in the kitchen in the summer of course. And a bigger one for the older ones. And the oldest of us used to wait until everybody had gone to bed and have ours. I have got a sister twelve months younger than myself and we used to al
ways have ours, let them all clear off to bed and we used to make ourselves some nice hot cocoa, we uses to enjoy our baths! Just once a week.
\par I:\tab There were seven of you?
\par MC:\tab Yes, there were eight. But we lost one little girl with meningitis at four.
\par I:\tab How many brothers and how many sisters`?
\par MC:\tab Five girls, two boys.
\par I:\tab So how did you all sleep?
\par MC:\tab Well in the back room, which was a fairish size, there was room for two double beds a
nd we had the four girls in the two, yes the four girls were in the two beds. And I think we had a little cot in that room for the smallest of the boys. Then we had another little cot in my mother and father's room for the other boy. But a bit later on we
 got a house, opposite to us in the back, with three bedrooms which made things very much better.
\par I:\tab How old would you have been then?
\par MC:\tab I should be about, I can't quite remember, but I should say about fourteen. But, when, we hadn't got quite so many chi
ldren when we had only the two bedrooms because I remember we had one little girl in 1918 and I was just 18. And I didn't know there were any more children coming! We had been in that house quite a year or two then so things were very much better with the
 three bedrooms.
\par I:\tab Had you any more garden in that house?
\par MC:\tab No, less.
\par I:\tab How old were you when your sister died of meningitis?
\par MC:\tab 18. She died in 1918.
\par I:\tab What sort of impression did it make on you?
\par MC:\tab Oh terrible, terrible. And she was the prettiest l
ittle thing, light golden curls. Really lovely, little girl. She was four, I think she was buried on her birthday, 31st October. Yes she was a lovely little kid. My father was, in the daytime he was a boilermaker on the old North Staffordshire Railway and
 then every night he played in the theatre orchestra. And sometimes after the theatre he would go on and play for an hour or two at a dance, well they called them balls in those days. And he had to go to work at six the next morning! Cornet player.
\par I:\tab Goodness. Would you see him when he used to play?
\par MC:\tab Well he was very strict but he was a good father. We saw him most at teatime when he used to come for his tea, and he used to have a quick tea and he used to get down on this big old sofa and he allowed hims
elf so many minutes to lie down before he had his wash and changed to go the - the theatre. And we had a wireless in those days, when wireless first came out, and he used to put it on before he laid down, and in no time at all he was fast as a rock, well 
y
ou'd say he was, and somebody would switch the wireless off and he would open his eyes 'What did you switch that off for?' and you would think he was fast asleep. He used to have so many minutes and he used to give one of us perhaps threepence a week, to 
clean his shoes to go to the theatre. He used to look lovely when he went out. We used to think he was the nicest man on earth you know.
\par I:\tab Which theatre was it?
\par MC:\tab He played at the old, he started at the Hippodrome, at Stoke, when it first opened. And tha
t must have been somewhere about 1900. The old ? Theatre, he started there. And from there I think he went to the Queens Theatre, Longton that was a theatre in those days. But he was at Hanley Theatre a good many years. And he has played occasionaly at th
e
 Grand, Hanley Grand. And then the Coliseum, Burslem, I don't know what happened there but they had an orchestra for something, I don't know whether they went a theatre for a while or what it was but he played at the Coliseum for quite a little bit. But h
e used to get up on Sunday afternoons and play with any band that would ask him to come and play. Excelsior Stoke on Military Band, any local band. They used to give concerts in the parks you see for charity.
\par I:\tab And he had any other outside interests?
\par MC:\tab Y
es, he had. You wouldn't think he could have, but he had. He had three allotments. And he kept us in vegetables and flowers. Yes. Mind you, he had plenty of children to go down and weed and do all that and give his orders. But we never went short of veget
ables, and flowers.
\par I:\tab Was orchestra playing mainly a financial thing?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes.
\par I:\tab Were your family short of money?
\par MC:\tab Well when he got married, I have heard my mother say this, when he was first married he got 18/- a week to keep a house on. And the re
nt was 5/2. It doesn't sound much but when it is taken out of 18/- it does, doesn't it? And of course they had got coal and light and food. And as soon as babies started coming along they had no help or anything like that in those days you know.
\par I:\tab Had your mother anyone in where she had a baby?
\par MC:\tab Oh there used to be just one old mid-wife, the district mid-wife. She had a doctor for me I believe because she used to tell me that he wanted to adopt me. And he would have given the world if shed had let me, h
e promised her, well he told her that she was going to have a lot of children and she would he having a baby almost every year, I don't know how he knew but she very nearly did, she had one every two years nearly for a long time. But she didn't want to, w
ell she wouldn't want the first to go. But there was this old mid-wife, used to go to anybody - who asked her to go, you know. Everybody knew her as the mid-wife.
\par I:\tab Had your mother worked before she was married?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes, she was on a factory, but I thin
k some kind of a shipping clerk. And she used to see the fun the girls had in the painting shops and she used to tell me about it, and she used to say I used to feel I was one on me own you know, stuck behind the desk and she said - if I had got any excus
e to go into the shop I used to love to go up she said and - I am sure that you will like it - when it first started, because you are so fond of drawing and painting. So of course that was that.
\par I:\tab Have you any idea of what your grandparents had worked at?
\par MC:\tab 
My mother was brought up by her sister, both parents died very young. And my father was brought up by an aunt because his mother died, at when he was three months old and his father died soon after. And he was brought up by an aunt. So there was no gra
ndparents.
\par I:\tab Had you any relatives who you would visit, or who would visit you?
\par MC:\tab In those days, yes. Me mother had a sister, she lived about ten minutes or quarter of an hours walk from us. But she was better off than me mother, her husband was a build
er and a decorator/contractor and they were all right. Not a nice house and greenhouse. I remember going up there and I think, when I come to think back, I think it must have been when me mother was having another baby. We wouldn't be old enough to know. 
B
ut Auntie Pattie would fetch two of us, that was Maud, the one next to me, and take us up to her house, but she used to have a nap every afternoon and she used to take us upstairs with her and I used to be in complete misery in this blessed bed, it was a 
h
uge four poster, and it had got curtains hanging at the side and I couldn't rest in the bed, I couldn't rest, and she used to be a bit annoyed you know because she used wanted to lie down and get a little nap. Oh yes, Auntie Pattie, and they went to Ameri
ca. They did very well. And me father's, got a sister in Yorkshire, they used to come over occasionally. And he had another sister in Durham. They were miners. 
\par I:\tab Had your father any jobs he would do about the house or would he just stick to the allotment?
\par MC:\tab 
Oh no. Well he made himself a great big wooden armchair. If you saw it when he finished it, you would wonder what, you could hardly pick it up to start with, it was that heavy. But me mother made it comfortable with cushions, home made cushions and th
ings like that. And this big old sofa. And made it comfortable with cushions and you could lie down and go to sleep on it, although mind you it isn't like what you get today. Oh yes he was very good. He hadn't a lot of time to do much you know.
\par I:\tab Would you help your mother a lot?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes, I can remember having to run home from school and she used to say 'Come home as quick as you can and clean the kitchen floor before your Dada comes back for his tea' he used to be in about ten past five, we used to lea
ve school at half past four those days. And I know I've run all the way home so the floor would be dry. You see she'd perhaps be washing and she'd have children running about, well she couldn't do it. Oh she'd not have any other help.
\par I:\tab She must have had a tremendous lot of work?
\par MC:\tab Oh she did yes. And no pleasure, 'till later life, and she had a wireless and oh she did love it. And - I have often had many a cry at the thought of, if she could have had a washing machine, things like that, and television.
\par I:\tab Had she any interests outside her home?
\par MC:\tab She hadn't time. The only interest she ever had was that she used to go to the pictures once, well not once a week, perhaps once a fortnight, sometimes in three weeks. And she used to take the three eldest of 
us in turn, one each, with her, to the pictures. But we couldn't afford a few sweets or anything like that. We used to cut a turnip up into little cubes, because me father had got plenty of vegetables. And these turnips were really nice, tasty, we thought
 
so, in those days. I don't suppose the kiddies would now, would they? We used to cut them up in squares and put them in a sweet bag or something like that and put them in a handbag and she used to hand them out. We used to sit there chewing the turnip, bu
t it was all right. If we were a bit flush we'd have a bag of peanuts from the man who used to shout peanuts at the door of the Old Princes at Stoke.
\par I:\tab Would you have meat every day or just on Sundays?
\par MC:\tab Oh we were very lucky with meat. Of course she was
 a woman who would get stewing beef, rather than steaks, I've known her to get stewing beef for us and make - and rabbit we've had hundreds of rabbits. Of course you can make such good meals, and she was a good cook. She'd either stew a rabbit and make br
o
th and then mince the rabbit up and make sandwiches for your tea, out of it, and perhaps have broth and vegetables for dinner. You see we'd always plenty of vegetables. And then on Sunday, me father used to buy two rabbits every Saturday night of his life
,
 when he was at the theatre, out of the market. The markets were open when you come out of the theatre in those days. He used to bring two rabbits home every Saturday and my Mother used to roast one and stew one and she used to thicken the stewed one and 
y
ou could either have roast rabbit with stuffing or stewed rabbit. But she did used to have a piece of beef, you know, something like that, occasionally. But we didn't have it very often but I know when she wanted to get me father a bit of something nice s
h
e - I've gone across to the butcher, he used to live opposite, almost opposite to us, for a quarter of beefsteak, very tender please. A quarter of beefsteak! That would be me father's. Ours, we've done with these beef soups and stews, but I suppose she'd 
think held get sick of that all the time. She'd done him plenty of vegetables with it. We've lived very well considering we had a big family and not much money.
\par I:\tab Would your father take sandwiches with him?
\par MC:\tab No, he wouldn't. He used to come home for his
 breakfast. His breakfast and dinner. He used to go to work at six o'clock and at twenty to half past eight, I think it was half past eight to nine, they had their breakfast and he used to come home and have a quick breakfast. Had to be on the table mind 
y
ou. And sometimes if, I don't know what happened, me sister and I have taken him his breakfast down to the works. And given him his breakfast, and he has gone back and had a cup of tea there. But every day he would come up for his dinner. Never had anythi
n
g at work. I don't think there was anything to have at work. And I know when he's come off the works at night, there have been children round the gate of the round house they used to call it, the railway works, they'd no shoes and stockings, saying 'Have 
you got a bit of bread left please?' Wasn't it awful? Of course most children couldn't, it wouldn't, it wouldn't seem believable, it would just seem a bit of a tale to them wouldn't it?
\par I:\tab Yes. Had you shops near where you lived then?
\par MC:\tab Yes. And one shop.
 We used to deal with one shop in particular. And we used to have a good order and my another used to pay for it every week, except Wakes week. Now they weren't paid for holidays and she couldn't save a penny a week, couldn't save it it, and on Wakes week
,
 on that week that she couldn't pay, I used to have go go with a letter, and I used to feel so humiliated and terrible about it, and ask if she could have the week's account spread over and pay so much a week out of it. Always used to say yes, because I m
e
an they knew how people were fixed. And each week, and I didn't understand for quite a long time, because I always used to go and pay the bill. And the top, it used to say 'Balance'and I used to think 'What's balance? We've had nothing called balance!' Bu
t
 each week she used to pay a few shillings a week off that balance 'till there was, and she'd soon paid it off. But at work, one girl that used to sit with us, she was a bit of a, they'd got a big family they had, and she said they used to have things, mu
s
t have had things like that and she was at school one day and the teacher said 'Now come out so-and-so and write down on the board what a bill would look like from your grocer, or wherever you get - your goods from' and this girl and or boy went out and w
r
ote it all down and the teacher said 'Oh yes, that is very good and Ivy put her hand up and said 'Miss so-and-so that isn't right' and she said 'Why isn't it right, it is right, what has he done wrong?' and she said 'He hasn't started with 'Balance' there
's always 'balance' on the top!' But they knew they'd get it you know, the shopkeepers.
\par I:\tab Would your mother ever buy food from the market place?
\par MC:\tab Well no, because she was never in the position to go down and get it because she'd got all young children a
nd she couldn't go out at night, my father was at the theatre you see. And she couldn't stand, well by the time I had come home from school and done me bit of 'Kale'it was only local shops we'd time to, although they didn't close in those days until goodn
ess knows what time.
\par I:\tab Were your parents strict would you say?
\par MC:\tab Well I can remember my mother being, she was brought up at a private school, and at one time I can remember when she used to be terribly, well not angry but she used to get on to me until I
 used to feel terrible about it. She used to say 'You're not to say 'ouse, you're to say house and pronounce words properly'. And she used to make me pronounce words properly. Which I did and I would do for quite a while, but then I'd go out and play with
 kids in the back and they would be talking so and so and I would be like them, you see. But I think she got in later life that she was fed up with trying to teach us all and I felt -
\par I:\tab Were they strict over table manners?
\par MC:\tab No, because they couldn't be.
\par I:\tab I suppose with seven children -
\par MC:\tab That's right. Especially the boys, they used to say - Mama can I have a piece of dripping they used to like, 'Can I have a piece of dripping - and she used to say - You won't want any tea - 'Well all right, and gives
 us pieces, all right'. And they'd run out, and they'd run out in the back or the yard or something with a piece. And they perhaps wouldn't even sit down for tea. But she kept us as strict as she possibly could. And they were very, they wouldn't let us sa
y
 a naughty word, a bad word, or anything like that. And I don't know how they kept their tempers, I really don't. I've known my mother to go upstairs and we used to sleep on flock beds in those days and she'd spread all the, clear a corner of the bedroom 
a
nd spread it with newspaper and shed tip all the flocks out of one bed while she washed the case, which she used to do pretty often, you've got to where there are children haven't you? Spread all the flocks out and one of us, well it wouldn't be one, it w
o
uld be more than one, would sneak upstairs and we'd play in these flocks. And we'd throw them at each other, and they've even landed behind the pictures on the wall! Everywhere and she'd gone upstairs and been ready to cry. You don't realise what you're d
oing do you?
\par I:\tab Were you ever punished at all?
\par MC:\tab No, I nearly was once. I'd got one little brother, and I was supposed to be looking after him, he was about two, if he was two, and I came in and me father said 
'Whereas Ernie? and I said He's come in' he said He hasn't come in, you've lost him! and I said He's come in he said He hasn't come in, you've lost him! and I said I haven't Dada, I am sure he's come in He's not come in. Well all the lot of us, all the fl
o
ck of us, had to go everywhere in every corner to try to find Ernie and nobody could find him. He couldn't be found. And I come in, and me father, I'd done it, I'd lost Ernie. And he lifted his hand up and he didn't hit me. But I fell down! And I fell dow
n
 against this old sofa and scraped me face and give meself a black eye but he hadn't hit me. And where Ernie was, I crept out, after that, I was so stunned and all that, that that I crept out and I went down some gardens, that we could see our windows fro
m
, and I saw a face at our bedroom window and I flew in because Ernie was so little that he didn't get upstairs himself you see. Or hadn't done up 'till then. And he sat in front of the window there, looking at horses and carts going by, no motors of cours
e
 in those days. And he was shouting - I'm upstairs and I thought I am sure that's our Ernie in our front window, and I went upstairs and he was shouting through the window Blood in your eyes he'd heard the carter swearing at the horses and he must have be
en saying some nice words to them, and it must have sounded like that to him. And he was saying Blood in your eyes to these horses. And he turned out such a lover of horses.
\par I:\tab Who made your clothes?
\par MC:\tab Oh me mother. Everything. I was fourteen before I had
 anything made. And me and me sister had a little black costume made by a dressmaker to go to Granddad's funeral, well me father's uncle, the one that brought him up, he died. And Maud and I had a black costume, that was the first thing we had made. But m
e
 mother made, made us, I don't know how she did but I know she used to buy yards and yards and yards of casement cloth and I remember her buying us, getting a roll almost of cinnamon brown, because she'd got five girls you see, of cinnamon brown and cream
.
 And she made us such sweet little frocks with cream collars and cream cuffs, with turn backs on the cuffs, and a little brown hat with cream upturned brim and it looked really nice. And I think my sisters got a photograph of us taken in a little pink nun
s veiling they called it, dress, that she'd made us all, nuns veiling dresses, and kind of rosette here with two pink silk ribbons and a pocket, to hold a pocket with a handkerchief in it.
\par I:\tab Would your father mend your shoes?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes, and my mother. And
 my sister and I did our own when we were about thirteen or fourteen. Had hands bleeding and goodness knows what but we did them. We went to a shop in Hanley in Pall Mall, walked up there and we've searched in a, there was a leather, a little leather shop
,
 I suppose it would be somewhere opposite to where Woolworths is now, and they'd got a big barrel of pieces of leather, and they were only perhaps 2d or 3d. a piece, you see, these pieces were, but we used to search until we could find two pieces big enou
g
h for a sole, at 3d. each, and two pieces big enough for the heels would be 2d, each and two penny worth of sprigs, I don't know whether they were sprigs or sprags, springs, we used to call the nails. Yes, I think they were sprigs, and we used to come hom
e and do them ourselves. We had got a last, one of those iron lasts, with a stand and two feet, a big foot and a little foot. Yes, we used to do our own shoes. And yes Dada and Mama used to mend all the other shoes in the house.
\par I:\tab Had you any spending money at all?
\par MC:\tab Yes, we had a halfpenny a week. And my, er me and Maud we always stuck together, we do it now, only she's smart and in good health you see, but still she's very good to me. One of us would buy a comic for a halfpenny and the other would have 
a halfporth of tin toffee, that two ounces. You got four ounces for a penny in those days and we'd divide the two ounces of tin toffee between us and then we'd both have the comic. Then we could change somebody else for a comic. You see go and change, one
 of the other children had bought a comic, go and change it, your comic for theirs so we'd perhaps have two or three comics and an ounce of tin toffee each for our halfpenny.
\par I:\tab Very good! Had your parents any books or newspapers in the house?
\par MC:\tab No, no. Me father used to take a daily paper and I used to try to read it.
\par I:\tab Which one was it?
\par MC:\tab I can't remember - oh the Despatch, the 'Daily Despatch'. But we had a, well he wasn't a relation actually, a relation by marriage, his father was a vicar, but I had
n't better say where, church, and he'd got a son, the youngest son, the others were married. And he was at the high School, and he used to come across, and oh he was a beggar this lad. I used to like him, mind you he was full of fun and all that. But he w
a
s a naughty boy. He used to come across and used to say 'Do me homework and I will give you a book' and I used to say 'Yes, all right' and I would do his homework, I used to love doing it, and he'd give me a Geography book or something like that. Oh and I
'
d did get it and love it. I can see this book now, the first one I ever had, and I won a prize, a photograph at school, for doing a map from memory and it was only through Eric's Geography book. And I remember going to this auntie's at the top of Leek Roa
d
 and in their greenhouse I went to talk to Uncle Tom, he was potting some plants and there was a big box under the sewage and it had got some books in and the top one was a big brown one and it had got two spheres. Perhaps an old at last of one of their c
h
ildren, mind you it was mouldy and stinking with being in this greenhouse, smelt of plants you know, but I used to sneak in there at every available opportunity I would delve into this - I could have had it I dare say but I wouldn't dare to bring it in be
cause it was smelly, you know.
\par I:\tab How old were you when you started school?
\par MC:\tab I was four, my sister was three, we went together. Cauldon Road.
\par I:\tab Was that fairly near where you lived?
\par MC:\tab Yes, yes. About four minutes.
\par I:\tab How big was the school?
\par MC:\tab Oh a n
ice little school, very nice school. An Infants School and then a big place, a bigger school for mixed Boys and Girls and then a smaller school for Standards 6 and 7 I think it was, or 5, 6 and 7. 6 and 7 I think. Yes, a very nice school and a good school
.
\par I:\tab Which were your favourite lessons?
\par MC:\tab Well there were two that I didn't like, and I had a smack for one, well hit at the back of the neck and I nearly hit him back, he was only a pupil teacher. History, I could not remember the numbers for the, dates 
of Kings and Queens, I couldn't. I felt I am not interested in Kings and Queens, I love countries and what they produce and all that, but Kings and Queens I just couldn't cotton on to them. And I couldn't answer a question on Kings and Queens and the pupi
l
 teacher gave me a hit like at the back of the neck, I nearly hit him back. I was glad I didn't after you know but I nearly hit him. And the other one was grammar and I always used to get mixed up with nouns and pronouns, things like that, I just couldn't
 
gather meself together quick enough. And we never called it English in those days, always grammar, having a grammar lesson one day, and they fetched me in to go to the doctor, the doctor used to come when you used to be ready to leave they fetched me out,
 
and the teacher said 'Ask the doctor when you're there what's the matter with you, why you know nothing about grammar!' I didn't mind yet I was nearly crying as I went out because I knew I was going this day because I was almost ready to leave school and 
