d, you know, no privacy or anything like that. He said 'I'am glad to see there is one sensible mother among you' and I thought I wonder who this is, and I was looking all round, and she said 'You, step out' and it was me. She said 'You are the only girl t
h
at is dressed correctly' oh I could have kissed me mother then of course. I thought I was the one in the wrong, you see. And very soon after that she sent a message to the headmistress, before I had time to leave, to ask if could go to be trained as a lad
i
es maid to a friend of hers in London. I think, I don't know what she was, I did know at the time, but my mother wouldn't let me go and I didn't want to. I was happy with a houseful of kids I was. I always remember going into a shop, me mother must have b
e
en having another baby at the time but I didn't know, I must have been dumb about those sorts of things because I didn't know when she was having them, I didn't. And many a time, even making nappies, and I said 'What are you sewing mum?' and she would say
 
Mrs Wood wants some new nappies for so-and-so's baby.' They'd be for her but I didn't know and I went into this shop and somebody had given her a cream flannel coat and she'd washed it and cut it up and made me a coat out of it. I thought it looked ever s
o
