u
rned to the other one and said 'She's the eldest of five or six (I don't know whether it was five or six) isn't it awful and I said 'Awful, what's awful about it?' I said 'It's lovely' and I come out and told me mum when I came home and me mother didn't k
now whether to grumble at me or what to do about it, but I remember it so well, I remember the woman. Oh isn't it awful' but in those days you either had them or you didn't have them! 
\par I:\tab Were your parents interested in education do you think?
\par MC:\tab Yes they 
were up to a point. I remember the headmaster sending for me when I was leaving school, Mr Pardoe, in the top school and asking me mother if I could go to Hanley, Hanley Higher Grade Girls, High School straight from school because he was quite sure that i
f
