\par I:\tab Had you ever holidays as children?
\par MC:\tab No, never any holidays. No. Me father was, he could get a free pass once a year, I think it was in those days, with working on the railways, but he could never take all the lot of us with me mother as well, because we coul
dn't afford a holiday, so he would take one or two of us to Liverpool, around the docks and those sorts of things, you know. Occasionally we had little trips like that, but I can only remember Liverpool, I think that must have been his favourite.
\par I:\tab Were your parents Church or Chapel people?
\par MC:\tab Well actually they were Church, but there was a chapel, Park Congregational Chapel near to in where we lived and mama said that if we wanted to go to that Sunday School we could go, we could choose our own. Well we 
liked it and we used to go to the Band of Hope at night, you know. And then we got in a class of elder girls and someone persuaded me to go to one of the other Churches, I won't mention which, and it'd had a hat given to me, well through an auntie. I didn
'
t think anybody knew about it, pale blue felt, and me mother had cleaned it up and made it look ever so nice, and I thought I will go to Church in this hat. And I heard somebody, as I passed by say to another girl - 'Oh she's got Elsie Ryder's hat on' wel
l that did it, I thought, oh dear, I'm not coming here again. Put me off altogether. So we just went when we felt like it after that. But I used to like it.
\par I:\tab Would all of you go?
\par MC:\tab Maud and I nearly went everywhere together. Because we paired off in twos, the family did.
\par I:\tab How about your parents, did they ever go?
\par MC:\tab No, they never went no. Well me mother couldn't, well me mother couldn't get dressed up on Sunday nights to go and a
s a matter of fact we had two visitors, a man and a woman, who used to come every Sunday of our life, every Sunday night, and me sister and I used to have to sing for them. Because there was no entertainment or anything like that you know. And we used to 
have singing for them, and we used to have a real good night, playing games.
\par I:\tab Friends of your parents?
\par MC:\tab Yes, I don't know how they had made friends, they just lived a few streets away. But without fail, and we had a big old fashioned clock on the mantl
e piece, dome shape it was, and me father used to, they used to stay and stay and stay, and he had got to be at work at six in the morning you know, and he used to draw a stool out and he used to stand on it in front of the fire and he used to say 'I am g
oing to wind this clock up because I think these people want to go home' and I don't know what time it was, and he used to do it every Sunday and they used to go. But they were there again next week.
\par I:\tab Were your parents strict over bedtime?
\par MC:\tab The young o
nes had to go to bed early, oh yes. And there the time would come when you'd got to, if I'd take one of the little ones to bed I'd got to lie there until they were asleep you know, things like that. And I can remember when we were very little me mother's 
s
ister that went to America left some kind of endowment or some kind of club to be paid every week, well she kept a shop before she went and she got quite a lot of debts so she told all these people to pay me mother the debts so that me mother could keep i
n
 benefit in this club for her. Well me mother couldn't get the money off them you know, they wouldn't pay in those days, they weren't forced to pay somebody who hadn't supplied them with the goods, and me mother wasn't the type to go knocking at the doors
 
and asking them for it. She just wasn't the type. So of course she didn't get the money, but at Christmas time Auntie Pattie used to send us, used to send me mother some dollar notes, that was to cover the club that hadn't had you see, and I remember one 
C
hristmas, and of course it got dark early, it must have been about seven o'clock and me mother was crying, said 'What's the matter?' and she said 'I haven't got anything at all for the stockings' of course I was the eldest and I was in with her and I knew
 
all her business sort of thing. She said What am I going to do, I have got apples and oranges, things like that, but I haven't got a present for the children, I don't know what I am going to do, it won't come now because it is too late' and I said Oh I do
n
't know, let's look round and try and find something to make something of. There is nothing else we can do' and we were talking like this and there came a knock at the front door, the postman with the letter and it - was late, because they must have been 
d
elivering late then. Or it may be because it was on the Christmas. But anyway when she opened this, me and her felt lovely. She says Run up Ada's as quick as you can' Ada lived in the next block and if ever Mama had to go to Stoke to fetch anything quickl
y
 Ada would come and sit in with us. Sort of baby sitter you know. She said 'run and ask Ada if she will come, quick' and I ran and brought Ada back with me. And she said 'Now come on down with me' and we went to Waites in Stoke, you won't remember that, t
h
ey had a shipping office and a big toyshop, combined, the shipping office was just round the corner. When we got there, they were about the only place to change these dollar notes, except the bank, and all the banks were closed of course then. And Mama sa
i
d 'We will go down to Waites'. We went to Waites and the door was locked and the shipping office was closed but the toy shop was open and we went on to the toy shop and Mr Waite was in the toyshop, the one who owned it, because they were busy, it was Chri
stmas Eve you see, so mama just had a few words with him and said she had just received this money and she would like to have a few toys, would it be all right, and he said 'Oh yes' oh and we picked the toys, oh it was beautiful, I can remember it now.

\par I:\tab How old would you be then?
\par MC:\tab I can't remember how old I was, I must have been perhaps eight or nine, something like that. Well young enough for me to want a doll. Oh and there was a beautiful doll with fair hair and I said 'Oh Mama and it was a shilling, 
a shilling and a halfpenny, or eleven pence halfpenny, well it was a lot in those days and I said 'Oh I should like that Mama' and she said 'Well I will tell you what, let's take that for Maudie because she hasn't been very well. You have the dark one bec
a
use Maudie likes fair hair better than you'. And I had to have the dark haired doll, I would have loved the light one, still I didn't mind so very much you know. They had wax faces and straw filled bodies, you know. And we bought something for each of the
 
kiddies, a present each for them. And we got home. And upstairs we had got a little ottoman, I think quite frankly it was originally an orange box, but it had been covered with things and nailed up and strengthened until it was a real good little ottoman 
a
nd there were three compartments inside and I remember the first night after I had the doll in the stocking, I put the doll in the first box, we had a fire in the bedroom, one of the children were poorly, I put the new doll in the first box of the ottoman
, and it came to the side of the fire, oh poor little face when I woke up in the morning! Oh I shall never forget it! It had got no face, it had all run you know, wax you know.
\par I:\tab Had you anything special at Christmas, did you have a bird?
\par MC:\tab Well I don't 
know because, yes we did have a bird as we got older. But I think when we were young, that I think Mother dressed rabbit up so much and stuffed it and browned it and made it look so nice that we actually thought we'd been having chicken. I'm certain of th
at, certain of it.
\par I:\tab Would your mother bake her own bread?
\par MC:\tab No. She wouldn't have time you know. I know what my father used to like when he used to come from the theatre, in those days you used to buy jam in stone jars, not glass jars, and she used to h
ave a big stone jar, two pound one I daresay it would be, and she used to get a Spanish onion and take the centre out and stuff if with a kidney, put a kidney in the centre of this and put a drop of water in it to step it from sticking to the side, not fi
l
l it with water, and just get the onion big enough to push down in the jar and cover it up and put it in the oven, the fire oven, until Dada came home from the theatre and he used to love that for his super. This onion, it had been in the oven for - but i
t was never burnt. They were very thick stone you know, and the kidney, when he cut it open, the juice used to run out, and it looked beautiful. There'd only be me and Maude and Mama up.
\par I:\tab It must have been fairly late by the time he got home?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes -
 yes. If she was tired, she'd had a big day, then she used to go to bed. Nobody had a key to that house, we had to just put a chair under the latch, she used to leave the latch on the door. It wasn't a door we opened at the side, it had got a knob in the 
middle, it looked all right, but you opened it from the side, but you used to do something and put a chair under it, you had only got to push the chair, push the chair they could have got in you know. Still we had nothing to pinch!
\par I:\tab How did you find your first job?
\par MC:\tab Well at that time there was a drummer in Dad's orchestra and he used to talk a lot about his wife working on Mintons. She was a band and liner and he used to say how she enjoyed her job. So Dada said, well they must have been talking it over
, him and me mother, and he said would I like to be a paintress to paint pottery, and I said 'Oh yes, I would love that' so Dada said You can't just walk in, you have got to go and see about it, get somebody to ask for you, speak for you. So he said 'I wi
l
l take you down Mrs Allens tomorrow, you and Maud' so we got dressed up and he took us down there and I got down there, we went the back way, she was in the kitchen and she was cleaning her kitchen floor (this was one of the things I told them on the talk
 
I had on the wireless) and she had got a striped petticoat on, very bright stripes, they must have worn them in those days, and she wore a black skirt, but she'd got the black skirt pulled up and pinned round the waist, but kneeling on a piece of sacking 
w
ith this very bright petticoat. I shall never forget that! So long, and so bright the colours were. And she'd got her hair pulled straight back, perhaps something like I am now, pulled straight back off her face, and I thought she looked so severe you kno
w
 and so strict. I thought, oh dear, this doesn't look very promising. Anyway Dada said 'I have come to ask you Mrs Allen if you will make enquiries on the works if they will take Madeleine on to start painting. 'Yes of course I will' she said, 'I will let
 
you know by John' that was her husband 'when I go to work tomorrow, and I will let you know by John.' So John come and Mrs Allen must have had a word with the old dear Mrs Kettle and she said yes, she would have me. She had a talk with her and she said ye
s
 she could bring, so I'd got to bring a pinafore, a clean pinafore, some clean rag and a knife. And a knife cost 1/4 in those days to grind your own colour with. And that nearly shook the life out of me for a bit, to think I had got to ask for that before
 
I could go to work. And when I got to work you were given a good big thick white plate and they gave you the - pencil that you worked with, nothing like the paintbrushes we'd ever used at school, they were very long and thin, and I thought I will never be
 
able to use that, never be able to paint with that. But you'd got to do, she did the first one for you, the old lady did, oh they gave you a tile and some powdered colour end same turpentine, and something called fat oil made from resin to make the colour
 
stick on the ware. And you'd got to, grind it up, and you got to grind it to a certain consistency it hasn't got to be too sloppy or too thick, just got to be this consistency, you have got to learn how to do that first, and you rub your pencil in, and, t
h
e first is only lines like that, getting smaller and smaller, but they have got to be quite regular, all the same thickness and the same distance from each other and you had got to cover the plate with that. So that was the first exercise. And then each t
i
me you had filled your plate you had got to clean it all off and start another one. And you had six of those and each one got more difficult. Well when you'd done that, you started to what they call shade. You had a broad pencil, and you blend your colour
 
just the same but you rubbed it in, your brush flattened out on the edge, and you rubbed it in gently down your tile so that one end held a lot of colour and the other end had none in and you put it round the flowers and made them look like real flowers y
o
u see, and you learnt to shade quite a while. And then there were some leaves, we would always work on this particular pattern called Hollins, Hollins Japan, and it was printed in very dark blue and coloured in red, it looked quite nice and they had a won
d
erful sale for it. They must have sold millions of pounds worth of it. Some of the leaves, a lot of leaves, it was a wreath and a centre on the plate, some of the leaves we had to do in dark colour and some of the leaves in pale colour. You'd do all your 
d
ark leaves first and then you'd wash some of the colour out of your pencil and rub it in a little bit of fat oil to make it smoother and then do all the other leaves in the pale colour. And you'd got to practice on that plate until you could do it perfect
l
y. And then you could go into colour, pinks and greens, and you'd got to work like that. You did that for twelve months and you got your two shillings a week not during that time, some of the girls were favoured and they had what was called the Irishman's
 
rise, you went round to the bosses office, which was on the floor lower down, an you swept his floor and lit his fire and you fetched him some clean water up and saw that his slop bucket was empty sort of, we used to call it kale, and you did his kale'for
 
him, and for that you got a shilling a week, that was wonderful! And I used to love it. Until one day I put my hand in a ewer, he used to keeps the patterns and things all over the shop, it was a rotten job actually, put my hand down to dust the inside of
 
a ewer and a mouse ran out! Oh dear. Well I nearly had a fit, oh I never wanted to go again. But I did go for a week or two but they all wanted to keep that job for the shilling. But anybody could have had that job for me! After that experience. It did re
a
lly frighten me because I mean I'd got my arm in and I wasn't thinking about anything like that and a blessed mouse ran up my arms. Anyway in the next shop, to ours was the missus of the women, of all of the women paintresses, and she had a kind of an off
i
ce, hers was a lot cleaner than his mind you, and she had a desk and then, what did I do for her? Miss Evans, she was a good old pal, a nice old lady, she wasn't all that old when I first went. I used to go in and do things for her. Oh fetch her - her wat
e
r, clean her hearth, light her fire, clean her hearth, fetch the water, empty the slops, and all that business, fetch a bit of coal up to keep the fire in, all that sort of business, and I got the shilling for that. And I was in there, I must have been in
 
there about three months, and all the other girls were ever so wild about it. And every morning she brought me a piece of cake to have with my lunch. She was a really nice person. But she was taken ill while s was there. And I had to, mind you I wasn't ge
t
ting on with my work, learning me own work, you see, but I caught up eventually, but I had got to almost sit in there and wait for everybody to come in and see what they wanted and so I could go and give a message to whoever, get in touch with whoever, yo
u
 see nobody would know who to go to if miss Evans wasn't there you see. Well I had instructions from the manager, if so and so comes for work, from so and so shop, tell them to go to so and so, I had got to tell them all this business. But I'd got to be i
n
 there you see for when they come. I lost a lot of time, but her sister worked in, two shops beyond that, and her sister still brought me the cake in and used to come and sit with me and have a talk. And when she was ill in bed, she was asking for me, Mis
s Evans was.
\par I:\tab Were they nice employers do you think?
\par MC:\tab Mintons? Well I worked twenty-four years on Minton and Mr John Campbell, have you ever heard of him? He was a real old pal, and he invited me to his house, but I never did go except to, when they, w
hat happened? I think he retired altogether and they gave him a scroll, and I went up with so many of them to present this scroll to him, to be framed you know, retirement and, but he used to come in our shop every morning, not every morning he used to co
m
e when he was well enough, he was very old you know in those days, and he used to come up and he used to sit and have a talk and a joke and a laugh and he used to say to me I can say these things to you and get away with it, you're a young woman and I'm a
n
 old man and it doesn't matter!' he said 'I'm old, I couldn't say these things to you if I was young!' and in my shop, there were only three of us in this shop at this particular time, there was a big old cupboard, well it was old, but it contained all th
e
 pattern books of the patterns that everybody worked on and whatever they wanted they had to come to refer to these books. Well as you opened the door, they were such dirty looking doors, I painted two pictures of - do you remember, you wont perhaps, Mabe
l
 Lucy Attwell little children, well do you remember the dogs, pugs with big heads. Well I did some of those, and - I did one holding the rose in his mouth and I left his paw on a litter, I forget what it was about and what was the other I don't remember. 
T
wo funny pictures. Anyway one day Mr John Campbell brought his grandson up, into our shop, and he said 'I want to show you something and I didn't ever know he'd seen these pictures because they were on the inside of the door. He says I want to show you so
m
ething, and this little lad went wild about these pictures and he as good as asked me for them but I don't think I gave them to him because I think they had been on so long that they were dirty, I think I did him two. And in return he sent me some scruffy
 
sweets, a piece of pear that had had a bite out of it, but he was only such a little boy, and it was quite sincere! Mr Campbell said, 'I've got something for you, I had to put it in a tin to bring it. I hardly like giving it to you but I promised to give 
i
t to you so I will have to give it to you.' He said 'Richard sent you these.' And they were sticky sweets and a pear. He said 'He is so pleased with his pictures that he feels he must give you something' so he sent me those. He was the one I got on best w
ith. Do you know Mr Haggar the one who used to come and have a cup of Bovril with us every morning.
\par I:\tab How many girls were there?
\par MC:\tab In the works?
\par I:\tab In your workroom under Mrs Kettle?
\par MC:\tab About twenty to twenty-four.
\par I:\tab Quite a lot?
\par MC:\tab From thirteen to a
bout eighteen. But you were not out of your time. You were not finished apprenticeship until you were twenty-one. And you were allowed money out of your wages until you were twenty-one. When you first started to go piece work after twelve months supposed 
t
o be tuition you were allowed 4d on the shilling and you were allowed that for, I think it was two years, and then you were allowed 3d in the shilling. For every shilling you got you had to give them 4d back and then for so many years 3d back and for so m
a
ny years 2d back and then. By that time you should be fully fledged by then. If you started when you were thirteen you'd got to work another twelve months because the girls started at fourteen just after I went and they were out of their time at the same 
time as me because you had got to wait until you were twenty-one in those days.
\par I:\tab Was it a fairly friendly atmosphere?
\par MC:\tab Yes, it was lovely, fun and -
\par I:\tab You got on well with them did you?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes. They were nice. I am in touch with 
some of them now. Yes, I have got a letter there from Canada. He's in America for a holiday. Two in Canada, one Australia, one in Plymouth, one up in Yorkshire, oh lots of them, I am having letters all the time from them. And if they come this way, and on
 
from Australia just walked in on me, and I'd just been washing, and I was really bad that day I must admit, and I gave her the wrong impression because I'd tried to make meself, I've got such a good husband and son, that I don't let meself go if I can hel
p
 it I try and do the best I can. I keep up. And I'd asked this day that Ivy come and they'd just gone back to work and I always get them their dinner, well I haven't been able to for some months 'till recently I have started again and I'd done a bit of wa
s
hing this morning and I really was all out, mind you, and I looked a sight, and I went to the door to her and she hardly knew me and she came in, and she wrote to me later how ill she thought I was and all this, and she writes now in a different vein than
 
she used to write to me and I can't bear it. She is sympathising with me all the time. And I don't want it! I don't want it! I'm better off than she is, she is parted from her husband. And had trouble with her children. I have nothing like that, I mean I 
can't grumble, I have worked fifty years.
\par I:\tab You enjoyed working?
\par MC:\tab 0h I did. It's marvellous what I used to do.
\par I:\tab What sort of hours were you working when you started?
\par MC:\tab Eight o'clock in the morning 'till one and we had 'till two for your dinner, you 
used to come home for your dinner, then work 'till six. But they had such a wicked old lodgeman when first we went, you weren't allowed to be late, you know. He would lock the door, he would come to the gate and see us running round Campbell's lace to be 
there dead on, and he would shut the gate in front of your face.
\par I:\tab So what happened then?
\par MC:\tab Well sometimes, they used to keep making different rules. Sometimes you would be off, they'd shut the gate for - for quarter of an hour, and then they'd knock som
ething off for it and perhaps they'd stop you half a day, perhaps they wouldn't let you go 'till dinner time, they used to keep making different rules as time went on. But oh I could have bashed that old man myself, and he'd shut the door, he'd see you co
ming, lots of girls, but I mean none of them, although we were very very seldom late, we had a nice bit of a walk.
\par I:\tab Were your friends still school friends or friends that you worked with?
\par MC:\tab Oh no school friends. No. I can't remember ever having any scho
ol friends. My son took us for a run well he takes us every Sunday morning, he is working on Sundays he's so busy, but before he goes and takes us, me and Dad for a run round Sandbatch, and places like that and I called at the farm for some peas and thing
s
 like I and I was talking to the farmer and he asked where I came from and I told him and he said 'I was brought up there' and I said 'Were you', and he'd - and he's lived in Valley Road where we lived and yet I can't remember him, I can't remember his na
me, but he is sixty-four and I'm sixty-eight you see. And it is a long time in a child's life.
\par I:\tab Would your mother mind who you played with?
\par MC:\tab Oh yes, she was very particular about that. But we'd some very nice friends, and a Welsh family and they'd got 
five girls, no boys, and they used to love one of us to go to sleep with them, either me or Maud, so that we could have some fun in the bedroom. And another girl, who lived a few doors above, she was one on her own, Dorothy. And we used to sleep with her 
v
ery often, either Maud or I, she didn't care which of us went, as long as one of us went. But she was always at our house. But there was one thing that I used to, and I didn't tell her but I used to tell Mama about it 'Mama you make me think you hadn't ou
g
ht to give Dorothy Wild what you give us' and she says 'Why?' she didn't like us to be selfish or anything like that and I mean if we only had half an apple or a little bit of chocolate or something like that, Dorothy would stand and watch us eat it, and 
s
he'd have exactly what we'd had and when we finished ours, we'd all finished ours, she's start hers. Oh it had used to annoy me! It did really! And yet we got on ever so well with her. Oh we had lots of friends. And when I started work, as I say, when I m
et Cecil on the works, through fetching these blessed ewers of water down at the tap down at the bottom of the works, he used to be washing boards for the dippers.
\par I:\tab What was his job exactly?
\par MC:\tab He was starting at the dipping house on Wintons. Mind you he -
\par I:\tab What did he do?
\par MC:\tab Well when first they were boys they used to have to wash all these big long boards that they put the ware on, keep them all clean and carry them to different dippers and take them to the ovens and things like that. And then of cou
rse the next, he could either have been a dipper or a placer, well he went to be a placer, and he worked forty-three years for one firm and they decided to go in with another firm, recently this is, Shorters'place it was, in Copeland Street, they went to 
W
heeldon somewhere up there. Shorters had ovens you see, they needed glasses and oven men well they hadn't, they'd got continuous kilns so they were all redundant and he never got a cent for that. This new rule came out about three weeks after it - and he 
had been there, he had been a boss thirty-five years, and he'd worked there for about forty-three.
\par I:\tab How did you first get to know him then?
\par MC:\tab Well he used to be washing boards and I used to go down for the water and he used to say 'That's heavy for you 
to carry, you know' - and I used to say, 'Well your jobs not so very nice either - you know', and we used to talk. Then one day he said - 'Will you come a walk with me?' I said 'A walk?' I think I was a bit dumb you know in those days and he says 'Yes' an
d
 I said 'Oh no, I play when I get home' I used to go home from work and do what we'd got to do and we used to go out and our backs was a triangular shape and at the top end, the broad end of the triangle was a stable, and oh we used to have some good game
s, lads and girls alike, all about the same age, you know, oh there used to be about twenty of us, of course there were three rows of houses you see and oh they were a nice lot of kids an all, and decent children, no spite or anything like that -
\par I:\tab When you were thirteen or fourteen?
\par MC:\tab Well from about twelve and we used to have huge romps across the backs and games of Fox give a loud Cuckoo and kickcan and all those sort 'Tivvies' with sticks you know, Tap on whips, oh all sorts of games, we used to have 
such fun, every night, until it was dark enough to go in. We had to go in then. Oh no - I said - I couldn't break the band up, we all play together - and he said 'Well can I come?' and he was two years older than me you know 'Well I said, you can come if 
y
ou like, but I said there is some of them younger than me and he said 'Oh I don't mind - and he used to come up and play with us at first. And then mum said to me one night who's this boy that comes up from Mintons, that hangs round you so much and I told
 
her all about him. And she said All right you can bring him in here, I will have a look at him before he goes home and I had to take him in, I couldn't tell her when I was taking him in, she wouldn't tell me when to take him in, and she was just bathing o
n
e of the little ones in front of the fire when we went in. But she made him quite welcome for a few minutes you know and she sized him up, and it was all right, yes, quite all right. And of course we went on walks, and very little else, because what with 
strikes and no work and short of work and all that we had very little money to spend, and then the war came, he was eighteen, he was called up in September and he was fighting in France in December.
\par I:\tab So you didn't see him?
\par MC:\tab No. He wrote all through the
 war you know. He came over on leaves you know, and we went out together then, we went walks, you know, beforehand. Our favourite walk was Shelton to Trentham, through Clayton and back through Newcastle wharf, all that way. Oh and when I had got new shoes
 on I was crippled, well we hadn't got the 'car fare of anything like that you know, we just walked.
\par I:\tab Would your mother mind you going out?
\par MC:\tab Oh no she didn't, we had got to be in for ten. Not a minute after ten. If it was light or anything, we'd have t
o be in for ten, I'd have to run many a time to get in for ten, and he'd come with me, and then later on we used to ask them in. There used to be, Maud had a boy, the one next to me, and May, the next one, we all three had boys and they used to, me father
 
finished at the theatres then, he lost a tooth, he was sixty mind you, he played - till he was fifty odd, all from twenties, he lost his tooth and of course he couldn't play properly, he was first cornet you see, solo cornet, he lost his tooth and couldn'
t play so he had to give it up and he was miserable at home at first at night, you know, he had got his garden in the day and all that but at the night he was itching for us to get in at night.
\par I:\tab At a loose end?
\par MC:\tab Yes, he didn't know what, there
 was no wireless or anything then. Although they did start to have crystal sets in glass dishes and things just about that time, but when the lads used to come in, mama used to make them a sandwich or perhaps a savoury duck and a spoonful of mashed potato
,
 or a bit of filleted haddock or something like that, a snack of some kind, and a cup of tea. Six of us, the three oldest grown-ups and the three boys you see and as soon as it was over, our dad was most impatient to get our supper and get the table clear
e
d, you know, Lotto came out, the lotto game, well that's the bingo it is now. And our dad used to love Lotto. And we couldn't afford to lose halfpennies. He used to say 'We'll play for halfpennies - well the lads could play for halfpennies, they'd got hal
f
pennies, but I'd got no halfpennies to spare and I used to say -I'll call - because the caller doesn't, I don't know how it was but Maud and May were more careful than me with money, if I'd got any money and anybody wanted anything they had it. You see wh
a
t I mean. I didn't waste money on myself but if - I'd got a few coppers I'd say to one of the younger ones fetch a pound of apples or plums or something like that from the shop. Well when they come I'd give all the kids one each see and well mine was near
ly gone then see.
\par I:\tab Would you hand over your wages actually?
\par MC:\tab 'Till I was eighteen. Then when we were eighteen mama said you know, you can start paying your own board.
\par I:\tab Would you have much money left over, that you could spend on yourself?
\par MC:\tab No, no,
 no. And when the lads came to tea then, we used to pay for the tinned fruit and salmon, whatever we had for tea, the girls used to buy it between them you see. Things like that. She was very good, they always made them very welcome, and they were the sam
e three lads that we all married.
\par I:\tab What I first wanted to sort out was the order in which your brothers and sisters were born?
\par MC:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab You were the eldest?
\par MC:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab And Maudie was?
\par MC:\tab Next to me, yes. A year and six days younger, and another siste
r a year and nine months younger, and then there was a boy, and then there was, er, Marje, another girl, then, and then there was another boy and then there was a little girl that we lost, and then the youngest is Dorothy.
\par I:\tab Have you any idea how old your father was when you were born?
\par MC:\tab No, I don't really know, but he must have been about, er, I should say he'd be about 27, as near as I can tell you.
\par I:\tab You said he worked as a boilermaker?
\par MC:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Had he always done this?
\par MC:\tab Yes. From a boy.
\par I:\tab And he did it?
\par MC:\tab On the railway.
\par I:\tab And he did up to when he stopped working? 
\par MC:\tab Yes. When he retired.
\par I:\tab Was he ever out of work?
\par MC:\tab Well, when they c - came to twenty one, when they came to twenty one they all had the sack then on the railway in those 
days, and they had to go out and find themselves another job, on a smaller factory, a smaller firm of iron workers or something like that, but they were all sacked at twenty one and then they were set on again afterwards, but they'd got to get themselves 
a
nother job in the meantime, I don't know why, but that was so, and my eldest brother was, er, the same, and the you - no, and, er, Jack was, er, the other brother, they both started on the railway and they both had to finish when they were twenty one, and
, er, my, they gave my eldest brother a job on the railway but away from here, but not doing his own job, he was only sort of cleaning lamps on railway stations and things like that, Manchester way, and he had to board out.
\par I:\tab What was his job?
\par MC:\tab He was, 
er, like me father, boiler making, but afterwards, when they set him on again, I don't know whether they set him on again, I can't remember, he went to do this job, which he didn't like, of course, and he came back home and I think he got a job at, um, th
e
 wagon works Hamley Shelton Wagon Works, er, but I'm not sure what he was doing there because it wouldn't be boiler making there, but it was in the iron, and the other brother is still, still on Shelton now, he was a riveter, it's all in the same, er, kin
d of work, yes.
\par I:\tab What jobs did your sisters do?
\par MC:\tab Well Maud came to work with me, yes, ah, because she wanted 'to come with me, we (were?) stuck there all our lives, yes, she came with me. Now the next, er, sister when she left school she started on 
the same place, but she didn't like painting, so she, er, me mother said she could go in a shop if she wanted to, so she did go to work in a shop, she sold, er, it was only a small shop, a house type of, er, shop, the people lived at the back, but they sh
e
, they sold a lot of cake and pastries and the woman made all (...) to sell in the shop, and May was in the shop there and also helped with the housework and all that sort of thing. Er, now the other two sisters were both on factories, they were both (...
) liners.
\par I:\tab Were all of them married eventually?
\par MC:\tab Oh, yes, they all married.
\par I:\tab What did their husbands do?
\par MC:\tab Er, Maud's husband, the next one to me, he was a warehouseman, he's just retired, er, May's husband was an engine driver, Marje's husband was
, um, one of, I don't know what you call them, one of these (...) cable men, takes, er, er, band of people out to, er, (...) cables and so on. Er, Dorothy's husband, he was on a factory in his younger days but he went to work afterwards, he was a polisher
 
on a factory when Dorothy married him, but afterwards he got a job on an iron works and got a bit of steel in his eye, and had to have his eye out, but, er, I don't think he picked any compensation up for it, but it was, er, they'd got to find him a job a
ll his life sort of thing, and he's still there.
\par I:\tab Would your mother be about the same age as your father when you were born?
\par MC:\tab Er, two years younger, I think.
\par I:\tab Did she ever work after she was married?
\par MC:\tab Oh, no, she never had a chance, because she ha
d, she had, I don't know whether it was one or two babies before I was born, yes, and they didn't live, she was married quite a few years when I was born, she was, must have been married about twenty, I think, and I'm not quite sure but I think she must h
ave bean about twenty-four or -five when I was born according to what, when I've reckoned her age up.
\par I:\tab The section on household routine. Did your mother always do set things on set days in the house?
\par MC:\tab Well, as a matter of fact washing was, er, three da
ys a week, well, not afternoon, not all afternoon but in the morning she used to wash and get the dinner, and then, er, the tub and the peg and so on would, er, be pushed under the kitchen table and she'd have to do coloureds the next day, sort of thing, 
because there was such a lot of us you see, yes, sometimes three days in a week, she'd be washing.
\par I:\tab Would she have baking days?
\par MC:\tab Well, she didn't do a lot of baking, she didn't, er, tart and things like, but that just came under the ordinary routine, it wasn't a baking day, you know, if we had a cake or tarts or anything like that.
\par I:\tab You told me that your mother made most of your..?
\par MC:\tab Oh, yes, she did.
\par I:\tab Did she ever buy anything? Would she buy your father's things? I suppose she'd have to, wouldn't she?
\par MC:\tab Well, yes, he had a, 'course he was in the theatre orchestra, you see, so he had to look smart, he'd got a tailor that we, that he always, that he'd had as long as I can remember, and this tailor, my mother had coats for herself from this tailor,
 she was measured for coats, and father was measured, he'd got to be smart at the theatre you see, and he was measured for suits, but of course it was paid for weekly, you see, came under the weekly payment business, and when Maud and I were old enough we
 were always measured, and we had a, a tailor made costume every year, that was our, our ration for clothes, we used to make our own blouses and underclothes, but we had a tailor made costume every year for, oh, a good many years.
\par I:\tab I realise your father didn't have much time in the house, but did he help your mother at all with making fires or anything like that?
\par MC:\tab No, no, he didn't, mind you, he couldn't, he wasn't in, because you see, he came for, er, finished work at five of clock and he came in, had 
his, washed his hands, and had his tea, and the first thing he did was to lie on the great big old-fashioned sofa, told you about that, haven't I, and he'd lie there and we'd all got to be as silent as mice, but one of them had to go in the kitchen and cl
ean his shoes for the theatre, and he used to have so many minutes and he knew exactly how many minutes he was allowed and then he used to go and have a right good scrub at the sink, because there was no bathroom, and get ready for the theatre.
\par I:\tab And that was every evening of the week except Sunday, was it?
\par MC:\tab That was, yes, every night, yes, and he managed to keep three allotments going, three allotments, I often wonder, mind you, we children did a bit of weeding and setting out and things like that, you know, we helped him, but..
\par I:\tab It sounded as if you helped your mother a fair amount. Did the other brothers and sisters do much in the house?
\par MC:\tab Well, I've only been saying today about this lighting (?) business for children, our hours were half past nine
 till half past twelve, and two till half past four, and Maud and I always had to run home from school, because one of us would always clean the middle room floor, and the other would be doing something else, either errands or setting the table or somethi
ng like that, but we did those sort of things, but she'd always got babies to look after, you see, she couldn't do a great deal of work. Mind you the house was never dirty, but it was rough, of course, with us lot in it.
\par I:\tab Did the older children help the younger ones with getting dressed, eating and mealtimes?
\par MC:\tab Er, not with getting dressed, I don't think, because while they were very little, me mother used to see to that, while we other older ones did something else, you see, but as soon as they were old
 enough they had to dress themselves, see they were forced into it because there'd nearly always be a younger baby then, as soon as they were old enough to dress themselves.
\par I:\tab It must have been a very hectic household.
\par MC:\tab You kn
ow, it was, it was lovely, we were all as happy as can be, oh, my sister came the other day, we were only talking about it, we never had much, nothing in the way of, er, bought toys or anything like that, but we always had, a good time, we had a happy, a 
really happy life when we were kids.
\par I:\tab When you were still at school did you have to go to bed at a certain time every day?
\par MC:\tab The other children did, but I didn't because I was the eldest, you see, and I was allowed to sit up, and of course I used to hel
p me mother a bit at night as soon as I was old enough doing bits of things at night, but the other children used to have to go to bed.
\par I:\tab Did you help with putting them to bed?
\par MC:\tab Oh, yes. (...) I used to go up with mother sometimes she'd perhaps be carr
ying one of the little ones, you know, and I'd go up behind the others and see that they got into bed because they used to dress, undress themselves in front of the fire in those days, and go up in their night-gowns.
\par I:\tab How old were you when you put yourself to bed?
\par MC:\tab You mean when I, you see, me father was out every night, so it made me mother that she'd want one of us for company, so I suppose that's more or less why I was kept up, because I most likely would have to have gone to bed, because they were 
very strict in their up -, er, in the way they brought us..
\par I:\tab (Question difficult to hear)
\par MC:\tab Yes, with the others, mm, and then when Maud got a bit older she used to say, er, you know, I don't want to go to bed, and mother used to say, well, all right, 
you two can stay up then because we were company for each other, yes, and then all the others and then, 'course, they'd have a crying match sometimes because somebody else wanted to stay up, but mum used to say no, you're to go to bed, she made them go to
 bed.
\par I:\tab Did you always have your meals in the middle room?
\par MC:\tab Well, there was only a front room, a middle room and a kitchen in that house, you see. At Christmas we had, er, meals in the front, oh, yes.
\par I:\tab Did you use the front room much or not?
\par MC:\tab Um, yes, on Sundays, mum used to put fires in and we'd go in, or if we had company, you know, we'd take them in the front room.
\par I:\tab When did the family have breakfast? Did you have breakfast as a family?
\par MC:\tab Well, no, mostly it was in instalments, really because
, er, there'd be, from when I can remember, um, we'd gather round the table of course, but one'd want, er, a round of toast and a cup of tea, and somebody'd want something else sort of thing, well the easier it got'd be, they'd be finished and they'd get 
r
eady and get off to school, you see, while someone else was finishing their breakfast, it wasn't a, a set come to the table and early to the table, it was a case of get in where you can, get your food and get off in the mornings. Er, in the afternoon, I d
o
n't there always seemed to be me and Maud and Mummy, that used to gather round together and then there'd be the younger children, but we should see to them first of course, and then Daddy used to come in, he used to have his by himself nearly always becau
se he hadn't got many minutes to spare, of course.
\par I:\tab So the younger children would have their tea first, and then you and Maud and your mother would?
\par MC:\tab Yes, yes, yes, have it after, yes.
\par I:\tab Did your mother bottle fruit or vegetables or make jam or anything?
\par MC:\tab 
No. She used to do huge jars of pickled cabbage, and pickled onions seven pound jars, so big and so heavy that they couldn't be lifted up and she used to have to put them underneath the back of the table there, and once we lost one, er, Ernie it wa
s one of the, er little boys, and, er, when we found him he was underneath the table in the pickle jar, with his arm in the pickle jar getting onions out. No, she hadn't got time for jam making and we weren't a - a jam family, you know, we were, no, we we
re more meaty and broths and -
\par I:\tab You'd have broth and soup for the midday meal, would you?
\par MC:\tab Yes, or she used to, er, do a lot of vegetables with having this these gardens, you see, we had plenty of vegetables.
\par I:\tab What sort of food would you have for the afternoon..?
\par MC:\tab Teas? Well it would be, um, well toast very often a lot, we had a lot of toast and mother would make an egg do between two of us, you see what I mean, something like that or cook some cheese and spread it on or something, all sorts of thi
ngs like that, nothing very expensive, but we always enjoyed a tea, yes.
\par I:\tab You said that your father sometimes had different food from you?
\par MC:\tab Oh, yes. Bit of steak, and, yes, mm.
\par I:\tab Would your mother always have exactly the same as you did?
\par MC:\tab 
Oh, no, oh, yes, the same as the children, yes. It was just me father she'd see to him first, he'd got to have, yes, and he used to love a sheep's head, and she used to make the broth and we kids used to have the broth and she'd make it look a bit present
a
ble because she put it on the table, but dad would eat all the meat out, out of it and she used to press the tongue and he'd have the tongue out of it as well, and the brains, sounds awful but it, it wasn't awful, wasn't bad at all. 'Course it was a meal 
in those days and rabbit, we had loads of rabbit.
\par I:\tab Did you ever say grace at mealtimes at all?
\par MC:\tab No, I'm afraid my father wasn't a very good churchman, he was a Catholic, and then he didn't get married at the Catholic church because me mother wasn't a C
atholic, they got married at Stoke Church, and the first time we met one of the Catholic fathers outside, I don't know what was said, but it was something that hurt me father a lot, so that, er, although he used to say sometimes if we lived nearer I'd see
 that you children were sent to the Catholic school, but I think it was more of a threat than anything else. I don't think he would have done really.
\par I:\tab What was your mother's attitude to manners at the table?
\par MC:\tab Oh, they were very keen on that, oh, yes, yes, and they wouldn't let us blow our nose in the house, go in the yard, things like that. Oh, yes, yes (...) times.
\par I:\tab Did they want you to hold your knife and fork in a certain way?
\par MC:\tab Oh, no, it wasn't, er, they weren't so particular about that, it was put on the table for you, of course, but I mean if you wanted to mash your vegetables up you could eat your vegetables with your fork, they wouldn't insist.
\par I:\tab Did you have to eat what your mother gave you?
\par MC:\tab Oh, yes, there was no question of, er,..
\par I:\tab No choice?
\par MC:\tab Oh, no, except when we got older, of course, when we got older we used to have on Sunday mornings my mother got a dish and it was, it was a fish dish actually, it'd be about sixteen inches long, and she used to keep it on the pantry shelf, t
he lower shelf and it used to hold chops sausage a bit of beef steak, kidneys, it was loaded with stuff for Sunday breakfast only, but it was for nine of us you see, and each one would choose their own breakfast, and of course the last to come down would 
h
ave to have what was left, and some of the breakfast we used to take upstairs, mm, if the lads wanted, er, bring us a couple of chops up with an egg, you know something like that, well, you see, er, we three elder ones, we'd want to get our share of the w
ork done, well, if they were drivelling down for breakfast all morning, you couldn't even clean up the kitchen, so we were glad to take it up to them so we could get on with the work and get it done.
\par I:\tab Would you say that your mother was an easy person to talk to and get on with?
\par MC:\tab She was the most patient, nicest person to speak to and she never raised her voice, er, she'd grumble if we needed grumbling at, you know, but, um, how she held her temper I do not know. She was most patient, she really was with
 us all, and she always used to say that, er, she wished we'd never grow up, she loved us all when we were babies, she did. She always said she never liked men, yet she picked one (..)
\par I:\tab Would you see your father much, or was he more of an absent figure?
\par MC:\tab 
No, we used to see him, oh yes, we had to be there and he had to know what, where, what you'd done and so, oh, yes. Oh, yes, we were all in, we used to gather round the window to see him come up the yard, er, from work, yes, oh, yes he wanted you to be
 there, oh, we saw him, and I used to set up every night for him, even if the others all went to bed, when he came from the theatre, yes, and, and I know we sat talking, me and Dad, till there hasn't been two coals of fire, glowing, and he's been telling 
m
e about the theatre and, er, erm, (...) and all those, he used to love that. The B.B.C. came and had a talk with him, he was, after he finished work, he couldn't rest at home, mind you he'd got his gardens, but it wasn't enough, he went down and did a bit
 
of, well he started to do a bit of fire watching, but it eventually landed up that he was working there during the day at the garage, near to the house, to where we lived and, er, there came, while he was there, there came someone from the B.B.C. to see h
i
m, they must have, er, heard about his musical experiences, but because he would insist they wanted him to, um, give a choice of music, he would insist there was nothing for him like Gilbert and Sullivan. Well, in those days, er, Gilbert and Sullivan, er,
 
everyone couldn't er, they - were something that only just been (...) this last couple of years, hasn't there, about the music, and they (...) they had to put it all out because he wouldn't, er, budge off it. He said that Gilbert and Sullivan music was th
e best he'd ever played.
\par I:\tab Would you say that your parents brought you up to consider certain - things as being important in life?
\par MC:\tab Oh, yes, I suppose so, there was only one thing they were a little bit lax about and that was, they didn't insist on us g
oing to a Sunday School, but they said that we could go if we liked to go, 'but we had got to choose our own. We started with a, with the chapel, thoroughly enjoyed it and then went to a church school because the other children, our friends, went, didn't 
enjoy it a little bit, and, er, when we got older Maud and I used to go to -the railway mission with a friend of ours and we loved that. People were so friendly and the atmosphere was so nice, little railway mission that had just started in Stoke.
\par I:\tab You were saying that your mother wasn't the sort of person that you could confide in?
\par MC:\tab Not intimate things, no she never, she didn't tell us about the, she didn't tell me anyway, about the facts of life, you wouldn't dare to say anything in the house that, er
, you wouldn't dare to try to make an opening for her to give you a word of advice, I didn't know anything about courses or anything like that until the night before I was thirteen and I slept with, er, a relation of ours, I always slept with her, well, f
o
r about a year, because there's only an old uncle in the house with her, and she told me in bed, and I was there the next morning, and yet me mother made a fuss of me and made me drink hot drinks and egg, whole egg on toast instead of half, things like th
at, you know, but, er, no, she wouldn't talk about anything like that.
\par I:\tab I would have thought that as she was having these babies every two years, that you would have cottoned on?
\par MC:\tab Yes, do you know that I was, I think I was eighteen, well almost eightee
n when her last baby was born, and I didn't know she was having it, I didn't know she was having it, because she'd always got a big, fairly big stomach, she was a biggish woman, she'd always got a fairly big stomach, and I really didn't know, and she must
 
have done all her sewing and everything when we were not in, in the day, you see, and put it all away, because I never saw a thing round the house, and she came and woke me up one morning and said, will you fetch Mrs Walley for me, and I said, oh, mum, an
d she says, go on, that was it, and I did not know, I don't know whether I was daft or what, but it was there, didn't know.
\par I:\tab Did your mother have any help when she was having the baby?
\par MC:\tab Help? No, she sat up in bed and cooked bread (??), yes we took the
 bread upstairs for her, we, you know, we were too young to cut it, 'course as we got older we could do those things for ourselves, but, I remember our Dad bathing us, the bath in front of the fire, you know, the little ones fetched the scrubbing brush in
,
 and the step stone and a big bar of, er, kitchen soap, to scrub the boys' knees with, and I said, oh, Daddy, you mustn't do that, you'll have no skin on them, he said, and he'd put the little girls' petticoat on back to front, and we were laughing, me an
d mother, having a good laugh, you know. We just watched him, because he was so, he didn't know the first thing.
\par I:\tab But he helped when..?
\par MC:\tab Oh, he helped if he could, 'course, yes, yes, but of course, he didn't have the time, he did what he could, of course.
\par I:\tab What did you do as a family on a Sunday, say, when you were all together?
\par MC:\tab When we were all little, do you mean? Well, um, we used to go for walks, er, children, perhaps thre
e of us'd go, or two of us, we'd go in twos or something like that for walks, and if we walked as far as, er, Trent Vale, we used to think we'd been to Trentham, it used to seem that far to us, you know, and we'd come back and say we'd been to Trentham, b
u
t in the cold weather I used to remem - remember those Sundays best, used to like those Sundays best, as Maud's been saying, we used to draw, all draw round the fire on Sunday afternoon and talk about things, and if we couldn't find anything to talk about
, we used to say, Mum, if we'd got enough money, could we have a shop, and she'd say, yes, what sort of a shop would you like, and then all our wits got to work, see, and everybody'd have a different tale to tell about the shop we were going to have.

\par I:\tab What were birthdays like?
\par MC:\tab Well, I'm afraid they weren't, er, recognised very much, they were recognised of course, but, er, we, they couldn't buy us anything, you know, no, didn't have presents.
\par I:\tab Had you anything special?
\par MC:\tab Er, perhaps make a bit of f
uss, you know, and Mum would make and say, well, it's Ernie's birthday today, you know, we'll have a cake or something like that, something we didn't very often have, a different kind, or something, but of course, she loved the lads, we used to say she di
d
, because she'd had three girls before she'd had a boy, and I think she thought she wasn't going to have a boy, you see, she used to love the lads, and she loved us all I suppose, but we had to, they wouldn't do a thing, the boys wouldn't in the house, oh
, no, and, and it was a sort of law in those days that boys and men, they didn't do anything, no, they didn't, and it wasn't expected of them, it wasn't it was always the girls and the women who had to get to.
\par I:\tab Did your parents ever play games with you at all?
\par MC:\tab Well, not, I, - in a way, of, of course they were not, er, father wasn't in you see, couldn't and every Sunday night we had two people to see us, I think I told you about that before, um, they used to come every Sunday night, so that, um, and in 
the summer he used to be down the allotment, till it was time to come in and have his tea, yes.
\par I:\tab You said that your mother used to read to you?
\par MC:\tab Oh, yes.
\par I:\tab Was it evenings when..?
\par MC:\tab Yes, when Daddy was, when Daddy wasn't in, you see, we'd draw up to the fire, and we used to say, read something to us Mummy, and she'd, she'd have to read what was in the house, if they were old books, it was just too bad.
\par I:\tab Did you have books in the house?
\par MC:\tab Well, she'd, she'd got some of her own, as I say, she'd go
t, er, they were such books as, er, The Three Musketeers and, er, The Mighty Atom, and, er, 20 Leagues Under The Sea and all those sort of books. She'd read out of those to us, but there were no more to read, but, er, before I was old enough I went to Ham
l
ey Library and asked if I could join, mm, and we used to go up and, Maud and I, we used to go from, er, I think we were in Leek Road then, Leek Road to Hamley Library two or three times a week, but we had all the fairy books there were in, the Green Fairy
 Book, did you have them, - yes, they were nice weren't they. We had all those, every one. We were always at the Library, and we got through them, 'specially me.
\par I:\tab Would you ever read out loud to the other children, or would you just read to yourself?
\par MC:\tab 
I used to tell the other little ones stories I used to make up, I used to love making them up, and they used to come and sit by me, the girls, not the boys so much as the girls, when the girls were little, they used to come and sit close, and they'd say, 
t
ell us a tale, tell us about Elsie, Elsie and the Milk Jug, a, - and I've forgotten the story, but I do remember the title and it was Elsie and the Milk Jug, and I used to tell them tales about anything that come in my head, I used to make a tale of it fo
r them. They used to like that. No I didn't read, because there was nothing to read to them, you see, only these old books, which were no interest to little children, no.
\par I:\tab You say that your father got a daily paper, did he allow you to read this?
\par MC:\tab Oh, 
yes, he never stopped us from reading them, oh, no, no, because it was, er, the Dispatch, I think that he used to have and - there was never anything in - in those - days that, er, that couldn't have been pasted up outside. I mean, there wasn't anything l
ike there is in the papers today, oh, no, they were quite readable they were, I used to read those of course.
\par I:\tab You said that your little sister died when you were eighteen?
\par MC:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab What sort of a funeral was it?
\par MC:\tab It was, er, what they call a sh-, s
hallow bier, um, the coffin went on the front of the, 'course, they were only for children, these were, in those days, horses, and, and it wasn't a big hearse, it was a big, er, (...) with a, a hall frame on the front of, they call a shallow bier, I don't
 
know why, er, and it just held the child's coffin, and it was covered with flowers, and then there was Daddy, Mummy didn't go, she, it, take it out of her, er, Daddy, me and Maud and, er a friend of Dad's, there was only about six of us I think that sat i
n this, er, but I remember ever so well the tears rolling down Dad's cheeks.
\par I:\tab Did you wear mourning?
\par MC:\tab Pardon? (Question repeated) No, not for Maisie, no the first mourning we had was for granddad when he died and I was fourteen then, and we had, Maud and I had a black costume made, black Melton (?) cloth, but it was nice.
\par I:\tab Did you ever get taken out to visit neighbours or friends or relatives?
\par MC:\tab Oh, yes, er, one of the schoolteachers used to take us to her house. They were friends of, we had an aunt
