t
o, Falden (?) Road, and she used to take, they left that house and went to live in, er, Regent's Road, I think it was, Fenton, or somewhere that way, er, a biggish house, er, she used to take me there for tea, Miss Wagg, and we had some more friends, they
 
lived down the bottom of (...) Road, er, their fa-, Lucy (and?) Marjorie Turner, their father was a sergeant-major in the, at the drill hall in Shelton, er, they were two very nice girls, and I used to love going there because Lucy used to take me, Lucy w
a
s the eldest, used to take me upstairs and she used to drag boxes and boxes from underneath the bed, with all sorts of things in, er, flowers to put on hats, and all those sort of things, little bits of wisps of er, of scarf, um, georgette wis-, oh, and I
 
used to be mesmerised with these boxes, because there was nothing like that in our house, it was just scrubbed underneath the bed, and they'd got carpet on the floor, you know, Lucy's and, really nice, you took your clothes upstairs when you went in, that
,
 that started it, it was very nice going there, oh, yes, we used to go out a lot, and we had a lot of friends, we'd always got somebody to come and have tea with us, yes, there's one girl who lived, um, few doors above us, she was the only one, she was ne
v
er happy unless she was with one of us, either me or Maud and, er, she'd come and her mother used to say if she only had dre-, bread and dripping at your house she used to thoroughly enjoy it, and, but she didn't want anything at home. She used to have br
ead and dripping very often, because we had and enjoy it.
\par I:\tab Had you ever any outings with your parents?
\par MC:\tab Very seldom, but Daddy could get free tickets, you know, er, from the railway once a year, but, er, the only place he ever took us to was Liverpool,
 and he used to like Liverpool, but he used to take us round and show us the, er, dockyard, you know, take us across the ferry to New Brighton, yes, that's the, only place he ever took us to. I didn't see the sea until I was twenty, no. I was twenty I had
 
me first holiday and Cecil came out of the forces and, er, asked me to go to Morecambe with his family, and, er, our Dad said no, not till either, this is how me father was, he said, oh, no, he said, not till either his mother comes to see us or writes a 
l
etter to ask if you can go, so of course I had to, I forget what happened, whether she ca-, I think she came and, to ask if I could go. I could go, I did go, I did enjoy it, oh, I did enjoy it. Specially after so long. Yes, never seen, mm, never seen the 
sea, I'd seen the, er, the Mersey, of course, at Liverpool, but it, er, I wasn't the sea, oh, I've seen some big seas there recently.
\par I:\tab When you were still a school child, how would you spend your Saturdays? Would you help your mother, or would you be playing out, or what?
\par MC:\tab Well, I don't think, er, we, the only place we went to play would be in the yard and we'd have to have one of the other little ones with us, you see, so there wasn't a lot of enjoyment for us, but, um, I must have been about, er, elev
en, I should say, er, when we were started to go to the pictures on Saturday afternoon, a penny, stand in a queue in deep snow till your feet were like bricks you know, for a penny, er, a pennyworth of the pictures, a little wooden picture place that was 
down at Stoke. Do you know where the Rialto is now, it was there, little tiny wooden place, the Queens.
\par I:\tab How many of you would go?
\par MC:\tab Er, just me and Maud. We, we used to do everything together and, so much so that she used to annoy me because, um, I, m 
slightly different natured than she is, well, she, she admits, but everywhere that I went she wanted to go, and I didn't always want her, but I had her, mind you, I didn't, er, create or anything like that, but, we, we started going with these boys, I met
 
this boy at the (...) I'm married to (him?) now, and, er, he came up to play with us, I told you about that, didn't I, and, er, she got in with a boy who also worked with Cecil and he lived down at the back of the station. Well, when they went in the forc
e
s, these people, this boys of hers mother used to send for us to go on Sunday afternoon for tea, and I used to say, Maud, you go, they're nothing to me, these (...) aren't, I said, they're nothing to me, um, I don't want to go, I said, you go, she said, I
'
m not going without you, and she wouldn't go without me, and I had to go and I didn't want to go, mind you, I was alright when I got there, but I'd rather have done something else, but, no, they used to send up every Sunday morning and they never said on 
t
he Sunday before, now you will come next week, won't you, sort of thing, they used to send two of their, er, a, boy, well, he was rather grown up, and a little girl on Sunday morning up to our house to ask us would we please come for tea in the afternoon.
 
We used to go there every Sunday, and then a bit later on when, er, I got, I got a friend who was a manageress at Halfords, and she used to send her brother for me every blessed Sunday dinnertime. I used to hate the sight of him coming up the yard, and I 
u
sed to say, ooh, Stephen, and I'd go anywhere, and our Mummy would never tell a lie, you know, and she used to say yes, I was in, and he used to say Helen wants to know if she'll come for tea, I don't know why because she'd got her own brother, my boyfrie
nd used to go, and yet she used to send for me on Sunday afternoon, I'd worked with her all week. You'd have thought she'd have had enough, wouldn't you.
\par I:\tab Would you always wear different clothes on a Sunday?
\par MC:\tab Oh, yes, yes we did have a best frock, and 
we always had, er, a special pinafore for Sunday with frills and soon, er, and we were allowed to wear that on Monday, on top of our school frock to go to school in, er, till it was dirty because we didn't dirty it out on Sunday, you see, and Mummy used t
o let us go in it on Monday, always go to school on Monday in your clean pinafore, course kiddies used to go to school in pinafores then.
\par I:\tab Would your mother let you play games on a Sunday?
\par MC:\tab Well, we didn't go outside, as I say the only thing that we di
d on Sunday was to go walks or go down to the garden, if it was fine we went down the garden (...) or for a little walk, something, no I don't think we did any playing outside on Sunday, I can't remember that we did, but we did plenty of playing in the we
ek. We would always got one of the kids with us, mind you, we were pretty well tied, but we had a good time.
\par I:\tab Had you ever any Sunday School outings at all?
\par MC:\tab No, er, Maud and I didn't but another sister did and she was left on (...) station, and Mummy 
said, I'll never let another, she was a, May, she's the third one, she was a small and quiet in those days and she went with them, er, on the Sunday School treat, and, um, they left her on the station, the treat come back and May wasn't on, they had to ke
e
p going and meeting the next train in and so on, you know. I don't know, she'd sit there quiet, you see, and nobody would be taking any notice of her, and that would be it, 'cause she was only little, and Mummy grumbled about it, she says if that's how th
ey look after you in Sunday School, you're as well not going.
\par I:\tab When you were still at school, did you go to any other social activities that were organised by the chapel or the church?
\par MC:\tab Oh, Band of Hope, we went, yes, oh, yes, I went to the Band of Hop
e, on Monday night I think it was, yes, we used to like that, used to say recitations, you know, but, as I say, er, religion got me down when I was small you know, when I was little I used to cry in bed because I used to think, er, I used to say me prayer
s
 Mummy used to say, now, say your prayers, you know, before you go to sleep, and, and I used to say me prayers and I though I used to think, I'm a hypocrite, I'm saying this and I don't love God best, I love me mother and father better than anybody, so I 
must be wicked, and I used to cry about it.
\par I:\tab What sort of age would you be then?
\par MC:\tab Well, I, I, I, it must have carried on quite a long time, it must have been as soon as I could register something like that until, well, it ca - I can't remember exactly 
when I stopped, er, I come to me senses, but, but it is silly, to the - teach children that, don't you think. Why should they love God the best, God's somebody we don't know, isn't it, I mean, you can't even picture God can you, you don't know what God's 
l
ike. If you're going to put him in person, he might be a black person or something like that, mightn't he. I think they should teach, er, children that it's just a being, it's just a being that's there, but, but they shouldn't talk about loving them, er, 
t
hey couldn't, they can, er, be obedient to them and all that and thank them for what they've done, and ask for blessings, but, er, er, to say that they must love them more than, for a child to love it more than its mother and father, I don't think that's 
right at all, and then you think if you don't do it, you, you're being, if you don't do that, you're being wicked and - 
\par I:\tab Was your father ever interested in politics at all?
\par MC:\tab Well, he used to argue about politics to one man and, er, he had, er, half of
 one of his gardens with him, he'd, er, got two and a half gardens, Dad had, and this man had half of one of Daddy's gardens and, er, he was a very big socialist, called them in those days, and I think Daddy was, er, hard and fast Tory, and, er, I've hear
d me father argue with him down the garden, my father made him look like a little worm when he was finished with him, but, er, I don't know about, um, he never talked about politics in the house, no.
\par I:\tab Had you any idea if he'd actually vote?
\par MC:\tab Oh, yes, h
e'd vote, Daddy would, because he, well he passed the school on his way to the theatre, you see, they used to vote at (...) School, well, he used to walk up to the er, well if he only walked to the, where they got on the tramcar he'd pass the school, oh, 
yes, he'd vote.
\par I:\tab But he hadn't an active interest? He wouldn't work for the Tory party?
\par MC:\tab Well, he had, he hadn't got a ha'p'orth of time to do anything (...) no, he couldn't do anything like that. I dare say he would have done otherwise because he was,
 er, he was well read, and, er, and he could, er, he could make his point, but it was all work and yet he enjoyed it, he did.
\par I:\tab What about your mother, would she vote as well?
\par MC:\tab I can't remember Mummy vot-, er voting, going up to the, no.
\par I:\tab Did she ever talk about politics?
\par MC:\tab No, not to us children, no, not even when we got older, she didn't. She might have talked to other people, because she had, she'd have friends to, used to come in to see her for an hour, you know, but, er, and she might have talk
ed to them, but, er, she'd never let us listen to conversations when women used to come in. She used to say, er, now you find yourself something to do in the front, because I don't think she liked us to hear gossip and, er, things like that.
\par I:\tab Would she have friends in as a regular thing?
\par MC:\tab Oh, no, not as a regular thing, no, and mostly in the day they wouldn't, er, perhaps, er
, there was, um, a policeman's wife and daughter and sh - and they used to come very often to see her, but they only used to live about two blocks away, but they'd just come and sit down and have an hour with her like yours for sitting down now, just sit 
and have a little talk and then they'd go.
\par I:\tab Did your mother ever manage to get out of the house at all?
\par MC:\tab Get out of the house?
\par I:\tab Yes, go and visit anybody?
\par MC:\tab Er, she used to come up to the school every Monday morning and bring us all a bit of lunch,
 and give it to us through the rails of the school, and, er, she used to walk round, that used to be at something past eleven, I think, when we used to have our lunch in the yard, school yard, and she'd have a little walk all round with, er, youngest, whi
c
hever baby was at home. She'd take them all round and then she'd meet us coming out and on the way back home she'd call at that house at those people who used to come on Sunday night, Bennet, Mrs Bennet, and we used to have 'bout half an hour there, becau
s
e Daddy hadn't used to come for his dinner an Monday till about half past two, he used to go straight from work to the theatre for the rehearsal, and, er, he very often bring a m - a musician home with him as well on Monday dinner time, for a meal, and th
en he'd have to pop off to work again and just (?) get a quick dinner, and ..
\par I:\tab So in fact your mother was housebound but she did manage to have some company?
\par MC:\tab Oh, yes, she, she never grumbled about being lonely or anything else, she never moaned about 
it. It's only in later life when you come to think back that you realise what a heck of a time she must have had, er, one thing I think now many a time, I do wish she'd had a washer and a television and things like that, I do, yes. She'd got a wireless as
 soon as they came in with the, er, glass dish and the, er, headphones.
\par I:\tab Did your mother and father belong to any of the saving clubs which were organised in those days?
\par MC:\tab They couldn't save a penny a week, no. As I say, I, I think I told you about it b
efore one week in the year she had to miss paying, er, yes, I mean if she'd have had savings that, they would have gone there, oh, no, they couldn't save because there was always one of the kiddies that wanted a pair of shoes or something every week out o
f that lot, oh, no, they didn't save.
\par I:\tab The other brothers and sisters, apart from Maud, how did you get on with them?
\par MC:\tab Well I shouldn't, I hadn't ought to say in case this ever comes out, but the next one, May, she came to see me one day last week, no,
 the week before and Maud was here on Thursday afternoon, um, I'm not very thrilled with that sister, I've gone weeks and not spoken to her when we lived at home, things, the tricks she's done and, er, things she said, you know, until Mummy said to me, sp
e
ak to her, oh, yes, she, she did nasty tricks, I don't know why, and yet she's made a good wife and mother and, and she, she came- to see me, brought me chrysanthemums and tomatoes out of the greenhouse, I can't, I, I never cottoned on to her, I don't why
, I hadn't ought to say it, but as I say it won't be, er, in print or anything.
\par I:\tab It's obvious actually that you were closest to Maud?
\par MC:\tab Oh, yes, yes, oh, well, as I say, Maud and I, we've done everything together, everything.
\par I:\tab You said you were at a railway mission?
\par MC:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab What sort of an organisation was that?
\par MC:\tab Er, religious, a little, er, a little place that they set up opposite to Stoke Station, it was only a smallish room, um, and er, it was this kind of, um, of place that when, er, they'd 
had a - a man to speak, er, to give a service who wasn't a, um, he wasn't he wasn't a parson or anything like that, he was just an ordinary man, but they spoke ever so, you could understand what they were on about, you know, it was really open for young p
e
ople, and you'd know everything that he said and digest it and it'd do you good, but when they'd, what I used to like, when they'd finished singing a hymn some old man'd stand up and say Hallelujah, God be praised, like they do at the Salvation Army, you 
know, and, er, I used to love that, I used to like to see somebody do that, you know, in the place, and somebody'd stand up and say a little prayer outwardly, and I used to think, how could they, but I used to enjoy it all the same.
\par I:\tab Were you still at school, then, or was this after you'd left?
\par MC:\tab I think I mu - we must have been about, um, twelve, I should think, perhaps I should be twelve and Maud eleven, it seems about like that when we started, but this girl got us to go, this girl that lived further 
up the road, that wouldn't (...) Dorothy Wild, er (her?) mother and father worked at the railway father was a guard and, er, he was called up and while the war was on her mother was a ticket collector at the railway.
\par I:\tab Did any of these neighbours or friends or relatives in fact ever help your mother if she was ill or expecting a baby?
\par MC:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Would you manage by yourselves?
\par MC:\tab Yes, we managed ourselves, Maud was the one who, er, stopped away from school, yes, because she got a good excuse, you see, she
 was subject to, um, bronchitis when she was young. Well, if you were away half a day the school board man used to come out to you in those days, to find out what was wrong. Well, they knew, I s'pose they get to know by your, your sheets which one, and th
e
n Mummy explained to the school board man that Maud was subject to bronchitis and if she didn't turn up it'd be because she'd got this, you see, well, she, she could sneak a day off for Maud where she couldn't for me, and Maud used to have a day off and, 
er, she was very good, Maud was.
\par I:\tab Were these Bennets your parents' main friends?
\par MC:\tab These Bennets? Er, they were the only people who used to come to the house, yes, mm, er, regularly come, you know, yes, yes a nice couple, they were. We were talking abou
t them last Thursday when Maud come. We used to dress up for them and, er, be theatricals, s'pose to be, you know, and sing and they always used to make us sing the part songs, we were, er, were taught at school because Maud sang, er, I was contralto and 
Maud was treble, part songs, we both got pretty fair voices.
\par I:\tab Did friends ever call unexpectedly?
\par MC:\tab Yes, I think so, 
yes, er, people would, er, come across, and one woman used to come, she used to come nearly every night, she lived further down the road, she used to go to work, but as soon as she used to come in from work she must have taken her clothes off, and yet she
 
passed the shop herself because she used to come to our house and she used to say to Mummy, can one of the girls go an errand for me, and either me or Maud'd have to go an errand for her, perhaps both of us, and she used to have a little talk to me mother
,
 twould be a little, er, way of getting out for half an hour and perhaps thought it'd do me mother good because she was a, a type of woman that'd make you laugh, you know that type, and she'd got a very loud voice. Mummy didn't like the way she spoke and 
all that, but she always had a laugh when she came, yes. She used to say, fetch me a quarter of corned beef and tell them to take all the corns out, and things like that.
\par I:\tab Did your parents' friends ever come for meals?
\par MC:\tab Mummy used to ask people to come
 for meals, we had one cousin who was going with, um, er, with one young lady and, er, they very often used to come for tea on Sundays, Ernie and (...) but he went to, er, America and he wrote for her to come to him, they were engaged when he went, and he
 wrote for her to come to him, and he'd got a home and everything ready and she decided she wasn't going to go out of the country and she wouldn't go. That was it.
\par I:\tab You have heard that many people split up the pre-1918 society into different social strata. Would you say this was so in the area where you lived? Were there very different sorts of people?
\par MC:\tab Different class of people, you mean? No, I don't think so, no, no we seemed to get on with everybody, everybody seemed to be same as yourself, yes, yes, I don't think there was, er, much distinction at all.
\par I:\tab But if you were asked to split people up in general, what sort of groups would you split them up into?
\par MC:\tab Well, of course, there's always the family where the kids have never got any shoes on their
 feet, er, and they go out dirty and untidy, well, we used to think there was no excuse for that, and we would avoid those children, not, perhaps the children'd be nice enough children, but the runny noses and things like that, you wouldn't, you know, y -
 
your instinct made you give them a miss, we wouldn't have anything to do with those kiddies, and the same type of boy, er, used to run me and Maud home from school, mind you, didn't matter because we had to run home in any case, but this boy used to run u
s, I think he thought we were frightened of him because we used to run but it wasn't that we were, we'd got to run home to do something, you see, and he used to run us, and we used to run harder if he was behind us, because we didn't like him.
\par I:\tab What about the people above you? What sort of people would these be?
\par MC:\tab Well, I never thought there was anybody above us, no, because we'd nothing to envy anybody for, because, we were poor admittedly, and, er, we'd got nothing, but, er, the people who had got some
thing, well, such as Lucy Turner, Turners had got plenty and all that, but, mind you, Mrs Turner used to send us lots of Lucy and Marjorie's old clothes down, me mother used to alter them to make them fit one of the family, she used to send parcels of bea
u
tiful things down that their kiddies had done with, and they were like new some of them, but, er, I never envied the Turners, I never envied them of anything and I didn't think they were any better than us although we, I thought they were lucky, you see w
hat I mean, I just thought they were lucky.
\par I:\tab What about the people like the doctor and the clergy and your teachers at school, these sort of people, would you feel them to be?
\par MC:\tab No, because we, they were most friendly with us, yes, except there was only
 one pupil teacher and he hit me on the back of the neck for nothing at all, yes, it stuck in my mind, that did, that was the only smack I remember having, er, no, they were so friendly the teachers were in those days, I remember going down to Stoke Churc
h to see one of them married and, er, she waved to me in all her get up, you know, oh, they were nice. Well, I thought all people were nice when I was little, I really did.
\par I:\tab Were you brought up to treat some people differently from others?
\par MC:\tab No, but me 
mother would say, I wish you wouldn't play with so-and-so, and I used to say, why, mother, they're all right, and she said, yes, well, they might be, but if you can get someone else to play with then just play with someone else, she wouldn't go into anyth
i
ng, explain what was wrong with them, but this very girl, the funny thing about it is that, this very girl that I remember that she always used to tell me not to play with went in a shop with me once, and pinched a carrot out of a basket, and, er, I thoug
ht, it's right what our Mummy says, she must be a thief.
\par I:\tab Were you brought up to call anybody Sir or Madam?
\par MC:\tab Oh, we had to call the teacher Sir, mm, oh, yes.
\par I:\tab Nobody outside school?
\par MC:\tab No, I don't think so, no I don't think there were any Sirs excep
t, er, the teachers, all the teachers were Sir, because we, Maud and I were in the top class all through the school and the top class was taught by a man and the, er, second class was taught by a woman, and we were (...). I suppose we must have been fairl
y
 good scholars, we were in the men's classes all through the school, mm, and they were nice, er, they were very nice men, they'd even give you a cough drop if you'd got a cough or something like that, you know, well you thought a lot about those things wh
en your're children.
\par I:\tab Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular social group?
\par MC:\tab No, er, I think me mother was a little bit too aloof, er, quite honestly, er, not that she ever said anything, but, er, she wouldn't encourage, er, -
 anybody to come in and, er, in fact she, there was one woman, little girl's mother that I told you, the bread and dripping girl, er, she used to come in and show off her shoes if she'd had new shoes, something like that, and she'd pick her leg up and lif
t
 her leg up and show her leg and our mum used to look so disgusted at her, you know, because she'd raised her skirt up and perhaps me father was sitting there, and our mum was ever so disgusted about it, and yet she hadn't used to say a word but I could r
ead her like a book, she didn't like anything like that, I think she was a very straight la-, I think they all were, you know, straight laced.
\par I:\tab Was your house rented?
\par MC:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you ever see your landlord?
\par MC:\tab Oh, yes, um they used to come, the one i
n Leek Road used to come every Monday, two old maids they were, that owned that, they used to come every Monday morning, I used to see them, Miss (...) French, I think they were, very nice they were, but they told me mother once that, er, they daren't do 
a
ny other but let us have the house when me father went after it because because he went straight from work with all this, in his overalls with the dirt on his face, and they said they were frightened to say no. He must have said that he, he'd heard that t
his house was coming empty or something like that and, er, he wanted to know if he could please have it, and they told me mother after that they daren't say no to him.
\par I:\tab What were they like as landlords?
\par MC:\tab Oh, they were all right, quite nice old ladies, they didn't do anything for us, er, I mean what papering there was done and things like that we had to pay for, yes. Oh, they were all right, there was never any bother.
\par I:\tab Did you ever feel that your parents were struggling to make ends meet?
\par MC:\tab 
They only time that that came forcibly over was at the Wakes (?) when they couldn't pay the grocery bill and I was the one who had to go up, ooh, and I used to feel terrible about it and I'd stand outside the shop for an hour, er, before I'd go in if anyb
ody was in, you know, waiting for the shop to empty, and it used to happen every Wakes (?), but it was soon paid off, you know, because you'd pay so much a week on the bill after that until it was paid for.
\par I:\tab Maud was saying that you had an opportunity of going to (...) High School, but your father wouldn't sign the papers. What exactly was happening?
\par MC:\tab Well, er, to start with, now that was in her time, that was two years after I left school, 'cause she had to stay till she was fourteen, you see, well, I 
should be fifteen then, well, I started work at thirteen, so I'd been at work two years then, but when I was thirteen, be - just before I was thirteen Mr (...) the headmaster sent for Mummy and asked if she'd let me go to high school, and Mummy said no, a
n
d I was there so I know what was said, there was no papers about it then in those, what, not in my case, but there probably was in Maud's, but as I say I was at work then so I didn't know, er, Mr (...) Mummy said no, she said, she's the eldest of so many 
a
nd what I do for her I'd want to do for the rest and I know that I couldn't afford it, so Mr. (...) said, well, it's a shame, to miss the chance, for her to miss the chance, and if you'll let her go, I'll supply her with all her books, I'll give her - her
 
books, but Mummy said, I'm sorry but, er, I couldn't let one go and not all the rest, and that's why I didn't go. Now, what happened with Maud, I don't know because I was working, and there probably was, there did come papers, didn't there, that you had t
o
 fill in you won't know, no, no, no, for this, supposed to be free education after, er, after school age, you had to fill in all the particulars of how much you earned and how much you spent on this and how much you spent on the other and how much of a fa
mily you'd got and why you'd got them and so on, and, er, old Daddy wouldn't stand for anything like that.
\par I:\tab Did your teachers at school emphasise anything as being important, like manners or punctuality or tidiness, this sort of thing?
\par MC:\tab Well, no, being
 men they wouldn't, would they? I don't know about the women what they told their class, but the men were very, um, down to earth with your paper and your pencil and get on with your work sort of thing, and, and you'd even, there was no, it wasn't even de
c
ent English in those days, like it is, must be now, it was a case of grammar, nouns and pronouns and adverbs and adjectives and take it or leave it, that's all that, there was no interest in, and I hated that blessed lesson, but I hated history worse, bec
ause I couldn't remember dates.
\par I:\tab Did the teachers punish children much?
\par MC:\tab Oh, yes, the boys had many a slap across the, got a cane, teachers had got a cane, a thin cane, seen the boys pull their arm back just when the stick's coming down, oh, yes.
\par I:\tab Would they punish the girls or not?
\par MC:\tab Yes, I think, er, the girls if they didn't do right they'd have a smack, wouldn't be much, you know, but they could humiliate you, the men teachers could, without giving you a smack, they'd only got to, if they - spoke
 cross to you it was enough, because the girls liked and respected these men teachers and they'd only got to speak cross to them and that'd be enough.
\par I:\tab Maud was saying your father never punished you, but he was sharp with you?
\par MC:\tab Oh, yes, oh, yes, he wa
s, mm, oh, no, he wouldn't, er, I, I, I don't remember ever, having a hit, I nearly had one once, I told you about that, didn't I, when I fell, yes, and he lifted his hand but it didn't drop, but I dropped. We had two teachers who were footballers for Sto
ke, Mr Mullineaux and um, Harry (...).
\par I:\tab Did the teachers single out some children for different treatment from the others, or did they treat them all the same?
\par MC:\tab No, they were awfully fair, oh, yes, there was no favouritism in those days, well, I never 
noticed any anyway, mind you, the, some girls in the class that you could secretly envy, in particular one girl that had got dark haired curls nearly down to her waist, and I used to think, how lovely Stella's hair is, I wish I had got hair like that, and
 
yet I'd got nice hair myself in those days, but it wasn't Stella's colour, it was dark (...) was, it was beautiful, and there was another girl who always used to come to school in winter and, er, it, I wasn't like it is now, and she always used to have a 
l
ovely cashmere jersey on, nearly a different colour two or three times a week,- you know and I used to think, ooh, Norah's got, must have some beautiful clothes, you know, but, you, I, we didn't, we weren't envious, we didn't wish we'd got them, but we th
ought how nice they looked.
\par I:\tab The children came from different sorts of homes then?
\par MC:\tab Well, not exactly, no, they were just ordinary terrace type, perhaps three bedroom and a bathroom, but, er, we never thought they were any higher than us in the social 
scale sort of thing, but they just dressed nicely, ooh, - they were in our class at school so that makes you one of them, doesn't it.
\par I:\tab There weren't any gangs at school?
\par MC:\tab Oh, no, there were no cliques either, not little cliques, no, oh, there didn't seem to be no, no snobbery, I don't remember any anyway.
\par I:\tab Your first full time job was when you were apprenticed?
\par MC:\tab Well, I started, I started on a market stall before that, you know when I was twelve, I told you, I had to tell a lie about it, did I tel
l you about that, oh, perhaps I told Miss, er, perhaps I told, er, Miss Hillman about that, er, we had a neighbour who used to manage a bazaar stall in the market and she asked Mummy if I could go and help on this stall, and I was only twelve, and Mummy s
a
id, would you like to go, and I said, ooh, yes, I would, so she, Mrs. (...) said to me, now you're not to tell anyone that you're not thirteen, because you're not allowed to work, and it worried me to death to start with, I'd got to go to work under a clo
ud because, in case anybody asked me I'd got to tell a lie, you see, and say I was thirteen.
\par I:\tab Was it a full time job, this?
\par MC:\tab Er, Sa - no, Saturday, all day Saturday, mm, from nine of clock in the morning till eleven at night for one and six, I think it
 was, but I loved it, but, oh, in the winter I used to come home at night half past eleven at night and my fingers used to be just like sticks used to have to hold them in hot water before I got any use in them, and sit with me feet in front of the fire f
or half an hour before they thawed out. It was a stall right in front of the doors and they'd pin, always pin the doors back in those days, oh, it was bitterly cold there, but I, I liked it, and then -
\par I:\tab Did you give your mother your wage?
\par MC:\tab Oh, yes, mm, it helped, you see, um -
\par I:\tab And when you started work you weren't earning very much?
\par MC:\tab Two shillings a week.
\par I:\tab Would you think it was a fair wage, that?
\par MC:\tab No, well, we knew it wa
sn't much, because, er, they used to talk about it at work, and some of the older women used to say you should grumble, we had to come to work for less than you get we, er, we used to come for tuppidy shillawick, and I used to say, what's that mean, two p
ence a day, a shilling a week, but they used to say tuppidy shillawick, and they used to have to buy their own candles out of that, if it went dark they'd got to light a candle of their own to work with.
\par I:\tab And when you started your other work?
\par MC:\tab Mm.
\par I:\tab How did you get on with the girls that you worked with?
\par MC:\tab Very well indeed, mm, very well, I .can remember every one of them now, real nice lot of girls, oh, they were not all perfect, you know, but taking them all together they were a nice lot.
\par I:\tab How did you feel about Mrs Kettle?
\par MC:\tab She was a splendid old woman to teach you, but she was an old tyrant, she'd walk down the shop and if everybody wasn't sitting up straight to the bench, you'd got to sit and hold your head back, work properly, she'd give yo
u a right good poke in the back and knock the front of you into the bench, oh, she was an old madam, she was, and she'd scratch, your d do, it'd take you I don't know how long to do a place and it, you'd think it looked lovely and she'd, you'd take it up 
t
o her, mind you, you realise afterwards that this is only to make you practise and practise and practise and she'd get that blessed wicked little penknife and give it a good scratch across your flowers and you'd not only got to wash that off properly but 
y
ou might rub all your leaves off as well while you were getting that off you see, you had to do it all again. Did I tell you about the whisky? Have you got time? I hadn't been there very long when, one day, I saw her do this, beckon me, I was down at the 
b
ottom of the shop and she sat at the top, only her bench came round the corner and she sat there looking right down the bench (?). She did this to me, so I went up to her and she pushed a little packet into me hand wrapped in newspaper, she said, go to Ja
c
kson's on the corner and bring me half a quart (-er?) of Johnny Walkers, so, I don't know whether she had quarter or quarten, not sure, but anyway I went where she told me to and it was whisky, this, oh, she says, and whatever you do don't let the lodgema
n
 see you either, go off or come back, so I had to go and fetch this whisky, and she kept this up for so long that the man in the bar used to bring me a stick of rock when he went away for his holidays and a bar of chocolate at Christmas (...) how long it 
w
ent on, and one day the lodgeman saw me sneaking back and he followed me up the shop and he came in the shop and he said, Mrs K., I've seen one of your girls and she's been off her work and I've seen her come back and she's got a blue spotted overall on, 
p
inafore, he said, a blue spotted pinafore on, and she looked so surprised and disgusted, she says, er, I don't think you have Mr Eton, he says, I know I have, he says, I know what these girls are, he says, and she's out of your shop, so she turned right r
o
und to a ever such a nice girl, Lily Shufflebottom her name was and she blamed her for going off her work, and carried on end stormed and said the next time it happened she'd have the sack, and it got me just rubbed up the wrong way that did, now if she'd
 
have kept quiet about it I wouldn't, It'd have I'd have, well, Id have tried to work in with her, because I realised she was an old lady and she had this in her tea and it perhaps kept her going, mm, cause she must have been getting on for seventy if she 
w
asn't seventy, I would have, I'd have tried to do something about it, but it just worked me up the wrong way, getting on to Lily because she knew it wasn't her, and I thought, well, for anybody to be so deceitful, so the next afternoon she sat like this w
a
iting for me to, and I never looked up off me plate, I worked and worked and worked and I never looked up till it was too late to send me, and the next day, um, at that time we used to have to stand with our backs to the benches when we wanted an order, w
h
en we'd finished the order we were doing we had to stand with our backs to the bench, and she'd tell you what to take, and I stood up with me back to the bench and I must have stood there, oh, an hour at a time, she wouldn't give me any work, I kicked me 
s
tool over to make a noise, you know, I did every thing, she wouldn't, er, wouldn't give me any work, that's how she got her own back, so there ca - settling day came, so I went up to settle and I got about half of what I had been earning and she'd got the
 
cheek to say to me when she settled, hmm, only so much, what have you been doing with your time, I said, you know what I've been doing with me time, I've been standing with me back to the bench, waiting for you to give me some work, and she says, you, don
'
t you dare to speak to me in that manner, I said, well, don't ask me, Mrs Kettle, such things as that when you know why I've got no wages, and she says, well, if you've got no wages your father ought to keep you till your twenty one, I said, well that's s
o
mething that he isn't going to do, I said, so you can take it from me I'm going home and I went straight up to me bench, I never served any notice, and I put me hat on, your hat hung on the wall in front of you on a sheet of newspaper, put me hat on, took
 
me coat from behind the door and walked out of the shop, and when I got out of the shop I realised that I'd got to go home and tell me mother I hadn't got any work, I didn't know what to do, so I was walking slowly home and I came past the Majestic pictur
e
 house and on the step there stood a man that I knew, named Mr (...), he was the manager at that time, and he said, hello, what are you doing, are you not working? I said, well, I've just walked out as a matter of fact, I said, I daren't, I daren't go and
 
tell Mummy that I hadn't got a job, he says, well, you needn't be out of work, he says, you can start here, he says, you can come tomorrow if you like, he says, I'll find you a job (...) out of work, so I thought, well I've done it now, I had to tell Mumm
y
 what I've done, so she says, oh, well, all right if that's it, that's it, 'cause I told her why, and everything, all about the whisky and, er, I went to work at the Majestic for a few months, but, it was all right and he gave me the balcony, you know, be
cause it was a bit - 
\par I:\tab How old were you then?
\par MC:\tab Um, should be about, er, seventeen, I think, yes, I should be about seventeen, perhaps sixteen, no I think I was seventeen.
\par I:\tab And you worked there a few months, and then what?
\par MC:\tab Yes, I went there for a 
few months, and Mummy didn't like me working there, she says, no, I don't like this, well, then, you heard me talk about Helen, that Stephen used to come and fetch me on Sunday afternoon Helen was the manageress at Halford's at Hanley, so Norman her other
 
brother worked in the operating box at the, er, Majestic and Norman used to come down and have a talk, we were old pals, he used to be at school with me, Norman, a nice boy, and he come one day and he said, Helen wants to know if you'll go and, er, work u
p
 at Halford's with her, and I said, well, I know Mummy would say yes, I said, because she rather me do anything than this, she doesn't like me coming here, so he said, well, you'd be all right with Helen, wouldn't you and I said, yes, I know I should, 'ca
u
se she was a nice person, you know, so I went and told Mummy, so Mummy said, yes, all right, you can go there, I'd rather you go there than work in a picture house, so I went to Halford's for a, but I wasn't there very long, and, er, I enjoyed every minut
e of it, mind you, oh, we had some fun.
\par I:\tab What sort of work was it?
\par MC:\tab A cycle accessories, you know, the Halford cycles, er, but they sold a lot of war things then, you see, the war had started and, er, they were selling, we sold cap badges and chevrons 
and everything for soldiers and we had a lot of soldiers in, I had two proposals over the counter, oh, yes, we had a good time, but, er, there came an old, the day that peace was declared, there came an old lady in in the afternoon, I took the place of a 
(
her?) boy who'd been called up, you see, this old lady came in and she said, er, we said how pleased, you know, about the war being over, and she says, yes, but, er, it won't be much pleasure for me, so I said, why not, she said, well they won't send for 
G
eorge back as long as they can keep you here and pay you less wages than they're paying George, so I thought about it and I thought, yes, she's quite right, they wouldn't, you see, so I said, well, I said, - wait a bit, so I went and had a talk to Helen, 
a
nd I said, George's mother's here, I said, and you know what she's just told me, Helen says no, so I told her, she says, well, she says, well I aren't going to say anything, she said, it's up to you to make the decision, so I said, well, take me notice, H
e
len, I said, I'm not going to keep that boy out of a job, so she, er, I went back to George's mother, I said, listen you can write and, er, if Halford's will apply for him because the firm had to apply for them then to get a demob, I said, if Halford's wi
l
l apply for him he can have his job, I'll give it up as soon as I can leave, well, in the mean time I went down to Minton's, er, Mrs K. had died, you see, and there was a new woman there, and I went down there and she said, oh, yes, come back and I went b
a
ck, 'course, I hadn't been out, I don't suppose I'd been out twelve months in any case, so I went back and everything was on the same old footing, yes, and I enjoyed the experience of those two places, I really did, I did, and I made a lot of friends, mm.

\par I:\tab You stayed with Minton's until you were married?
\par MC:\tab Oh, yes, I stayed there for twenty-six years altogether, - I left in 1939 and went to work for Spode.
\par I:\tab How old were you when you were married?
\par MC:\tab Twenty-four when I was married, yes.
\par I:\tab Would you rather have done any other sort of work?
\par MC:\tab No, I couldn't have had anything that I enjoyed more than me own work, mind you, I enjoyed me bit of weekend, er, serving, yes, I enjoyed it.
\par I:\tab Did you ever belong to a trade union?
\par MC:\tab Oh there was a Pottery Workers' Union in those days, yes, it started, er, I think it started when I was about, well, I remember it when I was about sixteen, I must have joined then, a few coppers, yes, Pottery Union.
\par I:\tab Were you actually actively interested in it or did you - ?
\par MC:\tab 
No, I was very disgusted with it because there was some kind of a, a strike, (...) I don't know whether it was a coal strike, but of course a coal strike affects, er, pottery workers, and, er, it, it came that the pottery workers were out because of the 
strike, and they paid a bit of, er, benefit, the Pottery Workers Union did, but when it - come to our turn to go there was no money in the kitty, but as soon as the start, we started work again, we had to pay a levy for what they'd paid out of so much a w
eek and yet we hadn't picked a ha'penny up and that annoyed me, I forget how we went on about it but I know I got me back up about it, but I used to go to meetings and er, listen to what they'd got to say, but I didn't always agree with them.
\par I:\tab Were you interested in politics at all at the time?
\par MC:\tab No, no, no I think I just, er, went by what me father said, if me father said so, that was it, sort of thing, he was right.
\par I:\tab Would you say that starting full time work made any difference as far as how you got on with your parents and your brothers and sisters? Did it seem to make a difference?
\par MC:\tab Not a bit, no, not a little bit of difference at all, I didn't feel any more grown up when I went to work, no, well I used to come home and play with the children in the back.
\par I:\tab Did you still help your mother in the house?
\par MC:\tab Oh, yes, yes, just as usual.
\par I:\tab Did you spend your Sun -?
\par MC:\tab Sunday? Oh, we worked till dinner ti
me, the girls did, doing the, we had a share of, of housework, see, which was allotted, each, and in the afternoon, we'd got the boyfriends, you see, then, when we started work, went for walks (...) bandstand, listen to the band.
\par I:\tab When you started work you spent your spare time in the way that you had before?
\par MC:\tab Yes, yes, except that, um, I made friends at work and they used to come for tea on Sunday, and, er, they said like Dorothy Wild used to say, I used to say, well, Ethel, you're quite, one girl in 
particular, you're quite welcome to come on Sunday if you like, but there won't be er, very much, you know, this week, she used to say, oh, it'll do for me, I'll come and they used to come, and we used to go to church after tea, we used to have a tea at h
ome and perhaps play with the kids in the afternoon, and Michael used to come with us, and then we used to go to church at night.
\par I:\tab Did you ever have evenings out at all?
\par MC:\tab In the week, do you mean?
\par I:\tab Yes, once you were in your teens.
\par MC:\tab No, I don't th
ink so, I don't think we, very seldom, er, Mummy'd take one of us to the theatre or the pictures, but we had to take it in turns, so that made it - it didn't come round very often, see, and the others had to stay in to look after the young ones.
\par I:\tab Did your parents like your bringing your friends home?
\par MC:\tab Er, yes, oh yes, they didn't mind a bit.
\par I:\tab In fact, did they want to meet them?
\par MC:\tab Yes, yes, especially the boyfriend, the boyfriend who insisted on coming and playing with us sort of thing, Mummy says,
 well, before you start that as a regular thing, I want to have a look at him and a word with him, 'cause I had to bring him, and I just brought him in, I didn't know what was happening and she was bathing the children on the hearth, still, I'm married to
 him, and he's the best husband that's on earth.
\par I:\tab Did your parents always expect to know where you were or where you were going and who with?
\par MC:\tab Oh, yes, yes, yes, and you g - even when, er, about when I was twenty I'd still got to be in at ten o'clock o
n Sunday night and we (...) if we were somewhere that we'd got to catch a bus or something like that, we'd got to hurry up home, be in for ten, mind you there was a bit of method about our Dad's madness in that time, he used to insist on us being in at te
n
, because after we'd had a bit of supper he used to like a game of Housey, Lotto, all of us round the table. Well, we couldn't start it until we'd all had the supper you see and the lads always had a sandwich and a cup of tea or something, have a bit of s
upper anyway, and Dad used to like to start to play, so I think he, he insisted on us being in for that, that as much as anything.
\par I:\tab You must have known your husband quite a long time before you got married?
\par MC:\tab Oh, yes, when I was fourteen, married when I was twenty four, but of course, the war was in between that, he went to the, he was in the First World War.
\par I:\tab Which of your parents did you tell first that you were going to get married?
\par MC:\tab Well, in those days you'd got to come and ask, you know, the bo
ys'd got to come and ask your parents, and I was twenty four, yes, said you'll have to come and ask Daddy, yes, well I told you I'd got to ask if I wanted to go to Cecil's family, with, er Cecil's family to Morecambe, yes, they expected you to, to ask, ye
s, he come and ask Daddy if we could get married, and Dad says, oh, I was there when he asked him, he says, well, I don't see why not, you know each other by now.
\par I:\tab How did you get on with your husband's parents ?
\par MC:\tab Oh, very well, especially old (?) moth
er-in-law, I got on very well with her, I nursed her with her cancer for a while before she died (...) yes. Oh, I got on very well with her, with both of them, but, er, the old man was a bit of a, one of those old men that, er, very erect, walk very strai
g
ht and he's, er, stern looking and all that and, er, when he's outside everybody thinks he's a perfect gentleman, but, er, on the quiet he'd wipe his feet on the old lady sort of thing, you know, that was, that was what happened in those days with the men
, they were lords of the (...) sort of thing, not like today.
\par I:\tab You said that you started paying your mother board when you were twenty one. How much did you give her of your wage?
\par MC:\tab I can't remember.
\par I:\tab Did you save up at all?
\par MC:\tab 
Oh, yes, yes, oh I saved and I bought blankets and things like that, oh, yes, I mean, you'd got to, you see, in those days, oh, yes, I saved, and then we bought our, er, all our own clothes, you see, underwear, and, well made them, didn't have much to sav
e, some weeks you had to dip in your savings to pay your board, 'cause you never knew how much your wages were going to be, you see, because it was a piece work job.
\par I:\tab It was erratic wasn't it?
\par MC:\tab Yes, you didn't know from one week to another and you'd have any work or no work or, and you'd got to find your board.
\par I:\tab It must have made it rather difficult?
\par MC:\tab Oh, yes, it was, yes
